The '''''Tiangong''''' '''space station''' ({{lang-zh|s=天宫|p=Tiāngōng|l=Heavenly Palace}}), officially the '''China Space Station'''{{Efn|The China Manned Space Agency refers to the station in English by the name '''China Space Station''', but English language news sources commonly use '''Tiangong space station'''.<ref name="cmse201311">{{cite web |date=5 November 2013 |title=集大众智慧于探索融中华文化于飞天 |url=http://www.cmse.gov.cn/art/2013/11/5/art_19_510.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210502062449/http://www.cmse.gov.cn/art/2013/11/5/art_19_510.html |archive-date=2 May 2021 |access-date=1 May 2021 |quote=最终决定沿用“天宫”作为载人空间站的整体名称，但后面不再加序号 |trans-quote=The final decision was to use 'Tiangong' as the overall name of the crewed space station, but without the serial number at the end.}}</ref><ref name="xinhua202104">{{cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-04/29/c_139914454.htm |title=China launches space station core module Tianhe |date=29 April 2021 |quote=The Tianhe module will act as the management and control hub of the space station Tiangong, meaning Heavenly Palace |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |access-date=29 April 2021 |archive-date=29 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210429040726/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-04/29/c_139914454.htm |url-status=live}}</ref>}} (CSS; {{lang-zh|s=中国空间站|p=Zhōngguó kōngjiānzhàn}}), is China's first [[Human presence in space#Living in space|permanently crewed]] [[space station]], in [[low Earth orbit]] since 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tiangong, China’s space station |url=https://www.planetary.org/space-missions/chinese-space-station |access-date= |website=The Planetary Society |language=en}}</ref> Operated by the [[China Manned Space Agency]] (CMSA),<ref name="Space.com 2023">{{Cite web |date=15 August 2023 |title=China's space station, Tiangong: A complete guide |url=https://www.space.com/tiangong-space-station |website=Space.com}}</ref> it is China's third space station, under the [[Tiangong program|''Tiangong'' subprogram]] of the [[China Manned Space Program]].<ref>{{cite web |title=China launches new Long March-5B rocket for space station program|url=http://en.cmse.gov.cn/news/202005/t20200506_46488.html|website=China Manned Space|access-date=26 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210617054112/http://en.cmse.gov.cn/news/202005/t20200506_46488.html|archive-date=17 June 2021|date=5 May 2020}}</ref> A [[Outline of space science#Astronautics|space laboratory]], it hosts experiments on [[bioastronautics]], [[Weightlessness|microgravity]], [[materials science]] and [[space technology]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 August 2023 |title=China's space lab starts formal operation |url=https://english.www.gov.cn/news/202308/19/content_WS64dffbb8c6d0868f4e8deab3.html |website=The State Council of the People's Republic of China}}</ref> Crews of three travel aboard the [[Shenzhou (spacecraft)|''Shenzhou'']] spacecraft for missions of about six months, with temporary crew sizes of six during handovers.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 December 2022 |title=China has 6 astronauts in space for the 1st time |url=https://www.space.com/china-six-astronauts-space-station-at-once |website=Space.com}}</ref> Cargo missions use the [[Tianzhou (spacecraft)|''Tianzhou'']] spacecraft. It is one of two operational space stations, alongside the [[International Space Station]] (ISS).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Space Stations |url=https://www.spacecentre.co.uk/news/space-now-blog/space-stations |website=National Space Centre}}</ref>

When China formally requested to join the [[International Space Station program|ISS program]] in 2007, [[Roscosmos]] and the [[European Space Agency]] (ESA) supported cooperation with China, but the [[Wolf Amendment]], enacted by the United States since 2011, prohibited Chinese participation. That same year, China launched ''[[Tiangong-1]]'', gaining [[Space rendezvous|rendezvous]] and [[Docking and berthing of spacecraft|docking]] experience. In 2016, ''[[Tiangong-2]]'' developed longer-term [[Life-support system|life support systems]], and autonomous docking and [[Orbital propellant depot|refueling]] via ''Tianzhou''. The current station has supported experiments involving researchers from 17 countries. It hosted the [[Lai Ka-ying|first astronaut from Hong Kong]], and China is training astronauts from [[Macau]] and [[Pakistan]].<ref name=":8">{{Cite web |title=Hong Kong, Macao astronauts set for their first spaceflight in 2026 |url=https://english.www.gov.cn/news/202504/23/content_WS68087d4ec6d0868f4e8f1ff9.html |access-date=13 May 2026 |website=english.www.gov.cn}}</ref><ref name="South China Morning Post 2026" />

''Tiangong'' is the third [[Space station#Architecture|modular space station]], after ''[[Mir]]'' and the ISS. Its core module, ''[[Tianhe core module|Tianhe]]'', was launched in April 2021 and was followed by the ''[[Wentian experiment module|Wentian]]'' and ''[[Mengtian experiment module|Mengtian]]'' experiment modules in July and October 2022;<ref name="nsf20210301" /> The modules were launched by [[Long March 5#Introduction of Long March 5B|Long March 5B]] rockets. The station has three [[robotic arm]]s in use and three external [[Chinese Docking Mechanism]] ports. ''[[Xuntian]]'', a [[space telescope]] scheduled for launch in 2027, is designed to periodically dock with the station for servicing and refueling.<ref name="Young 2022">{{cite web |url=https://interestingengineering.com/innovation/china-telescope-300-times-wider-hubble |title=China's giant space telescope will have a 300 times wider view than Hubble |website=Interesting Engineering |date=20 July 2022 |first=Chris |last=Young |access-date=5 November 2022 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105173422/https://interestingengineering.com/innovation/china-telescope-300-times-wider-hubble |url-status=live}}</ref> Orbiting at an altitude of {{Convert|340|to|450|km}} and [[Orbital inclination|inclination]] of 41°,<ref name="Space.com 2023" /> it has a pressurised volume of {{Convert|340|m3|ft3}},<ref>{{cite web |url= https://universemagazine.com/en/chinas-heavenly-palace-tiangong-space-station/?srsltid=AfmBOoq5WDHzbG074CXThrAUGlEndFY6yfTwqjLJ6_Vc8Ylv9mCbN1yc |title= Cristina China’s Heavenly Palace: Tiangong Space Station |last= Lytvynov |first= Mykyta |date= 19 July 2025 |website= Universe Magazine |publisher= |access-date= 24 March 2026 |quote=}}</ref> slightly over one third that of the ISS.<ref name="y955">{{cite web | title=International Space Station Facts and Figures | website=NASA | date=16 July 2024 | url=https://www.nasa.gov/international-space-station/space-station-facts-and-figures/ | access-date=2 April 2026}}</ref>

[[Shenzhou 12|''Shenzhou'' 12]] in June 2021 was the first crewed mission to the station. [[Shenzhou 15|''Shenzhou'' 15]] established continuous occupation of the station in November 2022 and completed the final major phase of station assembly. Later missions have focused primarily on scientific research. [[Shenzhou 23|''Shenzhou'' 23]] is the first attempt at a [[List of spaceflight records#Ten longest human spaceflights|year-long mission]].<ref name="BBC News 2026">{{Cite web |date=25 May 2026 |title=Li Jiaying: China launches first Hong Kong astronaut into space |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cn7p87r56mgo |access-date=25 May 2026 |website=BBC News |language=en-GB}}</ref> Tiangong is the first crewed spacecraft to use [[Hall-effect thruster]]s, for [[orbital station-keeping]], while communications are relayed through the ''[[Tianlian]]'' satellite network. {{As of|2026|5}}, 21 spacecraft have docked to the station: 12 ''Shenzhou'' and 9 ''Tianzhou''. Crews have made 24 [[spacewalk]]s, using the [[Feitian space suit|''Feitian'' suit]], including the [[List of longest spacewalks|longest spacewalk ever]], exceeding 9 hours in 2024.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Shenzhou 21 crew complete eight hour spacewalk outside Tiangong station |url=https://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Shenzhou_21_crew_complete_eight_hour_spacewalk_outside_Tiangong_station_999.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251222092109/https://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Shenzhou_21_crew_complete_eight_hour_spacewalk_outside_Tiangong_station_999.html |archive-date=22 December 2025 |access-date=12 May 2026 |work=Space Daily}}</ref><ref name="Jones 2024" />

== Nomenclature ==
Early names used in the [[Chinese space program]] were largely drawn from the revolutionary history of the People's Republic of China. In recent decades, these have been replaced by names with mythological or religious connotations. Examples include the ''[[Shenzhou program|Shenzhou]]'' ({{lang-zh|labels=no|s=神舟|p=Shénzhōu|l=Divine Vessel}}) crewed spacecraft,<ref>{{cite news |date=13 November 2003 |title=江泽民为"神舟"号飞船题名 |url=http://news.eastday.com/epublish/gb/paper140/40/class014000042/hwz1025144.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825171445/http://news.eastday.com/epublish/gb/paper140/40/class014000042/hwz1025144.htm |archive-date=25 August 2016 |access-date=21 July 2008 |publisher=东方新闻}}</ref> the ''[[China's spaceplane program|Shenlong]]'' ({{lang-zh|labels=no|s=神龙|p=Shénlóng|l=Divine Dragon}}) spaceplane,<ref>{{cite web |date=6 June 2008 |title=中国战略秘器"神龙号"空天飞机惊艳亮相 |url=http://shizheng.daqi.com/editor/slide/ent_slide/1761436/2.html#t |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223171321/http://shizheng.daqi.com/editor/slide/ent_slide/1761436/2.html#t |archive-date=23 December 2007 |access-date=21 July 2008 |publisher=大旗网}}</ref> the ''Shenguang'' ({{lang-zh|labels=no|s=神光|p=Shénguāng|l=Divine Light}}) high-power laser,<ref>{{cite web |date=7 September 2007 |title=基本概况 |url=http://www.siom.ac.cn/dirindex.asp?sdid=236 |access-date=21 July 2008 |publisher=中国科学院上海光学精密机械研究所}}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> and the ''Shenwei'' ({{lang-zh|labels=no|s=神威|p=Shénwēi|l=Divine Might}}) supercomputer.<ref>{{cite web |date=23 February 2003 |title=金怡濂让中国扬威 朱镕基赞他是"做大事的人" |url=http://news.sohu.com/07/30/news206713007.shtml |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609195758/http://news.sohu.com/07/30/news206713007.shtml |archive-date=9 June 2016 |access-date=21 July 2008 |publisher=搜狐}}</ref>

These mythological names continue in the [[Chinese Lunar Exploration Program]], whose probes are named ''[[Chang'e 1|Chang'e]]'' after the Moon goddess.<ref name="guardian.co.uk2">{{cite news |last1=Branigan |first1=Tania |last2=Sample |first2=Ian |date=26 April 2011 |title=China unveils rival to International Space Station |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/26/china-space-station-tiangong |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223092533/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/26/china-space-station-tiangong |archive-date=23 February 2020 |access-date=17 December 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> The name Tiangong was similarly reported to evoke cultural and romantic imagery, with the launch of Tiangong-1 inspiring public expressions such as love poetry, and media comparing the docking of spacecraft to the reunion of the cowherd and the weaver girl from folklore.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moskowitz |first=Clara |title=China's 1st Space Docking Inspires Love Poetry |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/wbna45140943 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602213921/https://www.nbcnews.com/id/wbna45140943 |archive-date=2 June 2021 |access-date=31 May 2021 |publisher=NBC News}}</ref>

In 2011, Wang Wenbao, director of CMSA, stated that the agency sought names that would "carry a resounding and encouraging" message and reflect public participation in the program.<ref name="guardian.co.uk2" /><ref name="theregister.co.uk">{{cite news |title=China sets out space-station plan, asks public to name it |url=https://www.theregister.com/2011/04/27/chinese_space_station_plans/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304033203/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/04/27/chinese_space_station_plans/ |archive-date=4 March 2016 |access-date=12 March 2016 |website=The Register}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=26 April 2011 |title=China asks people to suggest names for space station |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/et-cetera/china-asks-people-to-suggest-names-for-space-station/articleshow/8088114.cms |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214015803/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/et-cetera/china-asks-people-to-suggest-names-for-space-station/articleshow/8088114.cms |archive-date=14 February 2016 |access-date=27 January 2012 |work=The Economic Times}}</ref>

On 31 October 2013, CMSA announced standardized names for space station elements:<ref name="cmse-20131031">{{cite web |url=http://www.cmse.gov.cn/news/show.php?itemid=3743 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204175251/http://www.cmse.gov.cn/news/show.php?itemid=3743 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 December 2013 |title=中国载人航天工程标识及空间站、货运飞船名称正式公布 |trans-title=CMSE logo and space station and cargo ship name officially announced |publisher=[[China Manned Space Engineering Office]] |date=31 October 2013 |access-date=29 June 2016 |language=zh-CN}}</ref>

* Tiangong would refer to both the precursor space labs—[[Tiangong-1]] (2011) and [[Tiangong-2]] (2016)—and the modular space station.<ref name="cmse2013112">{{cite web |date=5 November 2013 |title=集大众智慧于探索融中华文化于飞天 |url=http://www.cmse.gov.cn/art/2013/11/5/art_19_510.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210502062449/http://www.cmse.gov.cn/art/2013/11/5/art_19_510.html |archive-date=2 May 2021 |access-date=1 May 2021 |quote=最终决定沿用“天宫”作为载人空间站的整体名称，但后面不再加序号}}</ref>
* Tianzhou ({{lang-zh|labels=no|c=天舟|p=Tiān Zhōu|l=Heavenly Ship}}) for the cargo spacecraft
* Tianhe ({{lang-zh|labels=no|c=天和|p=Tiān Hé|l=Harmony of the Heavens}}) for the core module of the modular space station, launched on 29 April 2021.<ref name="xinhuanet.com2">{{cite news |title=China readying for space station era: Yang Liwei |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-07/08/c_137310103.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708103339/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-07/08/c_137310103.htm |archive-date=8 July 2018 |publisher=Xinhua News Agency}}</ref><ref name="sn-201911012">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Andrew |date=2 October 2019 |title=This Is China's New Spacecraft to Take Astronauts to the Moon (Photos) |url=https://www.space.com/china-new-spacecraft-crewed-moon-missions.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230306004543/https://www.space.com/china-new-spacecraft-crewed-moon-missions.html |archive-date=6 March 2023 |access-date=1 November 2019 |publisher=SPACE.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=29 April 2021 |title=China launches core module of new space station to orbit |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-core-module-tianhe-space-station |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220928120340/https://www.space.com/china-launches-core-module-tianhe-space-station |archive-date=28 September 2022 |access-date=29 April 2021 |website=Space.com}}</ref>
* Wentian ({{lang-zh|labels=no|s=问天|p=Wèn Tiān|l=Quest for the Heavens}}) for the first laboratory module of the modular space station, launched on 24 July 2022.<ref name="Chinadaily201804">{{cite news |date=26 April 2018 |title=Planned space station details made public |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201804/26/WS5ae12347a3105cdcf651a87b.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220930060210/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201804/26/WS5ae12347a3105cdcf651a87b.html |archive-date=30 September 2022 |access-date=29 April 2021 |newspaper=China Daily |quote=The two space labs, Wentian, or Quest for Heavens, and Mengtian, or Dreaming of Heavens}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=24 July 2022 |title=China launches 2nd space station module to support science experiments |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-space-station-module-wentian |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220724092237/https://www.space.com/china-launches-space-station-module-wentian |archive-date=24 July 2022 |access-date=25 July 2022 |publisher=Space.com}}</ref><ref name="sn-201911012" />
* Mengtian ({{lang-zh|labels=no|s=梦天|p=Mèng Tiān|l=Dreaming of the Heavens}}) for the second laboratory module of the modular space station, launched on 31 October 2022.<ref name="Chinadaily201804" /><ref name="nsf_mengtian2">{{cite web |last=Beil |first=Adrian |date=30 October 2022 |title=China launches Mengtian science module to Tiangong space station |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/10/china-launch-mengtian/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031000653/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/10/china-launch-mengtian/ |archive-date=31 October 2022 |access-date=31 October 2022 |work=NASASpaceFlight}}</ref><ref name="sn-201911012" />
* Xuntian ({{lang-zh|labels=no|c=巡天|p=Xún Tiān|l=Touring the Heavens}}) for the co-orbiting space telescope module, scheduled for launch in 2027.

==Purpose and mission==
{{Update section|date=April 2026}}
According to CMSA, which operates the space station, the purpose and mission of Tiangong is to develop and gain experience in [[space rendezvous|spacecraft rendezvous]] technology, permanent human operations in orbit, long-term autonomous spaceflight of the space station, regenerative life support technology and autonomous cargo and fuel supply technology. It will also serve the platform for the next-generation orbit transportation vehicles, scientific and practical applications at large-scale in orbit, and technology for future [[deep space exploration]].<ref>{{cite web|title=空间实验室任务|url=http://www.cmse.gov.cn/|website=China Manned Space|accessdate=2 December 2008|url-status=live|archive-date=24 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124012258/http://www.cmse.gov.cn/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://science.howstuffworks.com/chinese-space-station-news.htm |title=What Does China's New 'Heavenly Palace' in Space Mean for the ISS? |website=howstuffworks |date=25 June 2021 |first=Patrick |last=J. Kiger |access-date=29 June 2021 |archive-date=29 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210629001833/https://science.howstuffworks.com/chinese-space-station-news.htm |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://thediplomat.com/2021/05/china-moves-toward-a-permanent-space-presence/ |title=China Moves Toward a Permanent Space Presence |website=The Diplomat |date=1 May 2021 |first=Namrata |last=Goswami |access-date=2 July 2021 |archive-date=9 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709182948/https://thediplomat.com/2021/05/china-moves-toward-a-permanent-space-presence/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

CMSA also encourages commercial activities led by the private sector and hopes their involvement could bring cost-effective aerospace innovations.<ref>{{cite news |date=11 March 2022 |title=China to open space station to commercial activity |url=https://spacenews.com/china-to-open-space-station-to-commercial-activity/ |access-date=18 March 2022 |website=SpaceNews |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Space tourism]] aboard the station is also being considered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-tiangong-space-station-tourism-plans |title=China plans to open its Tiangong space station for tourism within a decade |website=Space.com |date=22 March 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=5 November 2022 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105173421/https://www.space.com/china-tiangong-space-station-tourism-plans |url-status=live}}</ref>

China launched [[Tiangong-1|''Tiangong''-1]] in 2011, gaining [[Space rendezvous|rendezvous]] and [[Docking and berthing of spacecraft|docking]] experience.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 September 2016 |title=China launches spacelab, paving way to large station – CBS News |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chinese-spacelab-launched-to-pave-way-to-large-station/ |access-date=20 May 2026 |website=www.cbsnews.com |language=en-US}}</ref> In 2016, [[Tiangong-2|''Tiangong''-2]] developed longer-term [[Life-support system|life support systems]], and autonomous docking and [[Orbital propellant depot|refuelling]] via ''Tianzhou''.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 September 2016 |title=China launches spacelab, paving way to large station – CBS News |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chinese-spacelab-launched-to-pave-way-to-large-station/ |access-date=20 May 2026 |website=www.cbsnews.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Scientific research ===
[[File:Basic space experiment cabinet of Tiangong space station.jpg|thumb|alt=Basic space experiment cabinet of Tiangong space station|Basic space experiment cabinet of Tiangong space station]]
The space station will have 23 experimental racks in an enclosed, pressurised environment. There will also be platforms for exposed experiments; 22 and 30 on the Wentian and Mengtian laboratory modules, respectively.<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1493333813832736769 |user=TiangongStation |title=Once Wentian and Mengtian experimental modules dock with Tianhe, China Space Station will have in total 23 experiment racks on board. There will also be platforms for exposed experiments: 22 on Wentian and 30 on Mengtian.}}</ref> Over 1,000 experiments are tentatively approved by CMSA,<ref name="nature_un">{{cite journal |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-021-02018-3 |title=China's space station is preparing to host 1,000 scientific experiments |journal=Nature |date=23 July 2021 |first=Smriti |last=Mallapaty |volume=596 |issue=7870 |pages=20–21 |doi=10.1038/d41586-021-02018-3 |pmid=34302152 |bibcode=2021Natur.596...20M |s2cid=236213203 |access-date=3 August 2021 |archive-date=2 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210802171003/https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-021-02018-3 |url-status=live|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and scheduled to be conducted on the space station.<ref name="nature_experiments">{{cite journal |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-022-03462-5 |title=China's space station is almost complete — how will scientists use it? |journal=Nature |date=28 October 2022 |first=Smriti |last=Mallapaty |doi=10.1038/d41586-022-03462-5 |pmid=36307583 |s2cid=253204023 |access-date=29 October 2022 |archive-date=23 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221223183219/https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-022-03462-5 |url-status=live|url-access=subscription }}</ref>

[[Space farming|Agriculture in microgravity]] was explored with cultivation of [[rice]] and ''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]]'' as sustainable food sources for long-term spaceflight.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/tech/space-rice-china-tiangong-b2157386.html |title=China grows rice in space using new zero-gravity laboratory |website=The Independent |date=1 September 2022 |first=Anthony |last=Cuthbertson |access-date=5 November 2022 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105195915/https://www.independent.co.uk/tech/space-rice-china-tiangong-b2157386.html |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2022, the station completed the first complete [[agricultural cycle]] of rice in microgravity, from seed to harvest to seed replanting.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Singer |first=Peter W. |last2=Corbett |first2=Thomas |date=22 March 2023 |title=China ‘Colonizes’ Space with Its First Rice Harvest |url=https://www.defenseone.com/ideas/2023/03/china-colonizes-space-its-first-rice-harvest/384285/ |access-date=20 May 2026 |website=Defense One |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Firtina |first=Nergis |title=Chinese astronauts successfully grew rice aboard the Tiangong space station |url=https://interestingengineering.com/innovation/chinese-grew-rice-space |access-date=20 May 2026 |website=Interesting Engineering |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Chinese scientists complete rice, Arabidopsis life-cycle experiments in space |url=https://english.www.gov.cn/news/photos/202212/07/content_WS639057e2c6d0a757729e40b4.html |access-date=2026-06-01 |website=english.www.gov.cn}}</ref>

A novel bacterial strain, ''[[Niallia tiangongensis]]'', was discovered on the station in May 2023 during [[Shenzhou 15]].<ref name="Yuan2025">{{cite journal |last1=Yuan|first1=Junxia|last2=Zhang|first2=Wende|last3=Dang|first3=Lei|last4=Song|first4=Yan|last5=Yin|first5=Zhao|last6=He|first6=Ziwei|last7=Xu|first7=Kanyan|last8=Guo|first8=Pei|last9=Yin|first9=Hong|title=Niallia tiangongensis sp. nov., isolated from the China Space Station|journal=International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology|date=March 2025|volume=75|issue=3|doi=10.1099/ijsem.0.006693|pmid=40029317}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Jones|first=Andrew|date=21 May 2025|title=New species of space-adapted bacteria discovered on China's Tiangong space station|url=https://www.space.com/space-exploration/human-spaceflight/new-species-of-space-adapted-bacteria-discovered-on-chinas-tiangong-space-station|access-date=22 May 2025|website=Space|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Garay|first=Jorge|title=New Bacteria Have Been Discovered on a Chinese Space Station|url=https://www.wired.com/story/bacteria-unknown-on-earth-appears-on-chinese-space-station/|access-date=22 May 2025|magazine=Wired|language=en-US|issn=1059-1028}}</ref> The strain is particularly adept at [[Metabolize|metabolizing]] [[gelatin]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Yuan|first=Junxia|last2=Zhang|first2=Wende|last3=Dang|first3=Lei|last4=Song|first4=Yan|last5=Yin|first5=Zhao|last6=He|first6=Ziwei|last7=Xu|first7=Kanyan|last8=Guo|first8=Pei|last9=Yin|first9=Hong|date=March 2025|title=Niallia tiangongensis sp. nov., isolated from the China Space Station|url=https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40029317|journal=International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology|volume=75|issue=3|doi=10.1099/ijsem.0.006693|issn=1466-5034|pmid=40029317}}</ref>

The programmed experiment equipment racks for the three modules as of June 2016 were:<ref name="copuos2016tech20E">{{cite web |url=http://www.unoosa.org/documents/pdf/copuos/2016/copuos2016tech20E.pdf |last=Ping |first=Wu |title=China Manned Space Programme: Its Achievements and Future Developments |publisher=[[China Manned Space Engineering Office]] |date=June 2016 |access-date=28 June 2016 |archive-date=5 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705055504/http://www.unoosa.org/documents/pdf/copuos/2016/copuos2016tech20E.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref>
* Space life sciences and biotechnology
** Ecology Science Experiment Rack (ESER)
** Biotechnology Experiment Rack (BER)
** Science Glove-box and Refrigerator Rack (SGRR)
* Microgravity fluid physics and combustion
** Fluids Physics Experiment Rack (FPER)
** Two-phase System Experiment Rack (TSER)
** Combustion Experiment Rack (CER)
* Material science in space
** Material Furnace Experiment Rack (MFER)
** Container-less Material Experiment Rack (CMER)
* Fundamental Physics in Microgravity
** Cold Atom Experiment Rack (CAER)
** High-precision Time-Frequency Rack (HTFR)
* Multipurpose Facilities
** High Micro-gravity Level Rack (HMGR)
** Varying-Gravity Experiment Rack (VGER)
** Modularized Experiment Rack (RACK)

=== Education and cultural outreach ===
The space station features space lectures and [[popular science]] experiments to educate, motivate and inspire the younger Chinese generation and world audience in science and technology. Each lecture is concluded with a question-and-answer session with school children's questions from classrooms across China.<ref>{{cite web|title="天宫课堂"第一课定于12月9日下午在中国空间站开讲，此次太空授课活动将进行全程现场直播|periodical=Mp.weixin.qq.com|publisher=|url=https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/gQkzsxQBJEDW7zQQTuCjPw|format=|access-date=|last=张馨方|date=6 December 2021|language=zh|pages=|quote=|archive-date=6 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211206172316/https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/gQkzsxQBJEDW7zQQTuCjPw|url-status=live}}</ref> The first and second Tiangong space lesson was conducted in December 2021 and March 2022, as a part of the [[Shenzhou 13]] mission.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-tiangong-space-station-astronauts-science-lesson |title=China's Shenzhou 13 astronauts stream live science lecture from space station |website=Space.com |date=17 December 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=20 October 2022 |archive-date=20 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221020194718/https://www.space.com/china-tiangong-space-station-astronauts-science-lesson |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/04/shenzhou-13-return/ |title=Shenzhou-13 mission ends with safe return of Chinese taikonaut trio |website=NASASpaceFlight |date=15 April 2022 |first=Tyler |last=Gray |access-date=20 October 2022 |archive-date=20 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221020194719/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/04/shenzhou-13-return/ |url-status=live}}</ref> This tradition continued with the [[Shenzhou 14]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/chinese-astronauts-science-lesson-tiangong-october-12 |title=Watch astronauts give science lesson from China's space station early Wednesday |website=Space.com |date=11 October 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=20 October 2022 |archive-date=20 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221020194720/https://www.space.com/chinese-astronauts-science-lesson-tiangong-october-12 |url-status=live}}</ref>

The CSSARC is the Amateur Radio payload for the Chinese Space Station, proposed by the Chinese Radio Amateurs Club (CRAC), Aerospace System Engineering Research Institute of Shanghai (ASES) and [[Harbin Institute of Technology]] (HIT). The payload will provide resources for radio amateurs worldwide to contact onboard astronauts or communicate with each other, aim to inspire students to take interests and careers in science, technology, engineering, and math, and encourage more people to get interested in [[amateur radio]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://amsat-uk.org/2022/03/17/amateur-radio-payload-for-the-tiangong-space-station/ |title=Amateur radio payload for the Tiangong space station |website=AMSAT-UK |date=17 March 2022 |access-date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=18 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220318161126/https://amsat-uk.org/2022/03/17/amateur-radio-payload-for-the-tiangong-space-station/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hamsatsa.co.za/2022/05/08/upcoming-amateur-radio-payload-on-the-tiangong-space-station/ |title=Upcoming Amateur Radio Payload on the Tiangong Space Station |website=HAMSAT ZA |date=8 May 2022 |access-date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=3 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103142426/https://www.hamsatsa.co.za/2022/05/08/upcoming-amateur-radio-payload-on-the-tiangong-space-station/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

The first phase of the payload is capable of providing the following functions utilising the VHF/UHF amateur radio band:<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-03-17 |title=Amateur radio payload for the Tiangong space station |url=https://amsat-uk.org/2022/03/17/amateur-radio-payload-for-the-tiangong-space-station/ |access-date=2026-06-03 |website=AMSAT-UK |language=en}}</ref>

:* V/V or U/U crew voice
:* V/U or U/V FM repeater
:* V/V or U/U 1k2 AFSK [[digipeater]]
:* V/V or U/U SSTV or digital image

== Structure ==
''Tiangong'' is a third-generation modular space station. First-generation stations, such as the early ''[[Salyut]]'' and ''[[Almaz]]'' stations and ''[[Skylab]]'', were single-module outposts that were not designed for resupply. Second-generation stations, including [[Salyut 6|''Salyut'' 6]] and [[Salyut 7|7]] and ''Tiangong'' 1 and 2, incorporated docking ports that enabled mid-mission resupply. Third-generation stations, such as ''[[Mir]]'' and the [[International Space Station]], are modular complexes assembled in orbit from multiple components launched separately. Modular design can improve reliability, reduce costs, shorten development cycles, and support more diverse mission requirements.<ref name="nsf20210301" />

