=== Modules ===
[[File:Rear view of Tiangong Space Station.jpg|thumb|alt=Rear view of Tiangong Space Station, taken by Tianzhou cargo spacecraft ahead of docking.|Rear view of Tiangong Space Station, taken by a [[Tianzhou cargo spacecraft]] ahead of docking.]]
[[File:HK WCN 灣仔北 Wan Chai North 香港會展 HKCEC 創科博覽 InnoTech Expo 天宮太空站 Tiangong Space Station December 2022 Px3 10.jpg|thumb|A mockup of ''Tiangong'' displayed in Hong Kong in 2022]]

Tiangong was completed in a three-module configuration in 2022. China has proposed several expansion concepts. Initial proposals called for enlarging the station to six modules by duplicating the original trio,<ref>{{cite web |date=20 August 2021 |title=Astronauts conduct second Chinese space station spacewalk |url=https://spacenews.com/astronauts-conduct-second-chinese-space-station-spacewalk/ |website=SpaceNews}}</ref> but by 2023 this evolved into a plan to add a fourth module with six docking ports to accommodate future growth.<ref>{{cite web |date=28 February 2023 |title=China to expand its space station, international astronaut selection underway |url=https://spacenews.com/china-to-expand-its-space-station-international-astronaut-selection-underway/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702162133/https://spacenews.com/china-to-expand-its-space-station-international-astronaut-selection-underway/ |archive-date=2 July 2023 |access-date=12 March 2023}}</ref> In October 2023, China announced a revised roadmap to expand Tiangong to six modules beginning in 2027.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Andrew |date=4 October 2023 |title=China to send new modules and co-orbiting spacecraft to Tiangong space station |work=SpaceNews |url=https://spacenews.com/china-to-send-new-modules-and-co-orbiting-spacecraft-to-tiangong-space-station/}}</ref>

The [[Tianhe core module|''Tianhe'' core module]] provides life support and living quarters for three crew members and houses the station's guidance, navigation, and orientation control systems. It also contains the main power, propulsion, and environmental control systems. It is based on the Russian [[Functional Cargo Block]].<ref name="indexarm" /> ''Tianhe'' is divided into three sections: living quarters, a service module, and a docking hub. The living area includes a kitchen, toilet, fire suppression equipment, atmospheric control systems, computers, scientific apparatus, and communications equipment for contact with ground control in [[Beijing]]. ''Tianhe'' also carries the Core Module Manipulator (CMM), a large robotic arm used for EVA support and as a backup for module relocation. A full-scale mockup of ''Tianhe'' was displayed at the [[China International Aviation & Aerospace Exhibition]] in Zhuhai in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.spacechina.com/n16421/n17212/c3327307/content.html |title=Airshow China 2018: Chinese space station module makes public debut |website=China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation |date=29 September 2021 |author=CGTN |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025220859/http://english.spacechina.com/n16421/n17212/c3327307/content.html |url-status=live}}</ref> CMSA videos have shown that two core modules have been constructed.{{Citation needed|date=November 2025}}

The first of the two [[Laboratory Cabin Module|Experiment Modules]], ''[[Wentian module|Wentian]]'', provides additional avionics, propulsion, and life-support capacity as backups to ''Tianhe''.<ref name="s14_wentian" /> It includes three short-term crew quarters for use during handovers<ref name="reuters_wentian">{{cite news |date=24 July 2022 |title=China launches second space station module, Wentian |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/china/china-launches-second-space-station-module-wentian-2022-07-24/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221102030023/https://www.reuters.com/world/china/china-launches-second-space-station-module-wentian-2022-07-24/ |archive-date=2 November 2022 |access-date=2 November 2022 |website=Reuters}}</ref> and features a dedicated airlock for [[extravehicular activities]] (EVAs), replacing the temporary use of ''Tianhe''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s docking hub, which was not purpose-built for that function.<ref name="wt_airlock">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Andrew |date=14 July 2022 |title=China prepares for July 24 launch of second space station module |url=https://spacenews.com/china-prepares-for-july-24-launch-of-second-space-station-module/ |website=Space News}}</ref> ''Wentian'' carries internal experiment racks and 22 external experiment adapters.<ref name="s14_wt_2" /> It was launched and docked with ''Tianhe'' on 24 July 2022<ref name="docking" /> and moved to its permanent starboard position on 30 September.<ref name=":0" />

The second experiment module, ''[[Mengtian module|Mengtian]]'', provides expanded in-orbit experiment capability with 13 internal experiment racks and 37 external experiment adapters.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ling |first=Xin |date=12 October 2022 |title=China's space station prepares for new frontiers of science with launch of Mengtian module |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3195718/chinas-space-station-prepares-new-frontiers-science-launch |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221027140320/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3195718/chinas-space-station-prepares-new-frontiers-science-launch |archive-date=27 October 2022 |access-date=25 October 2022 |website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> It also features a dedicated cargo airlock designed specifically for transferring scientific payloads between the station interior and exterior.<ref name="xinhua_mengtian">{{cite news |date=1 November 2022 |title=九问"梦天"——详解中国空间站梦天实验舱发射任务 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/tech/20221101/a16de507cf514c6283c75e2e9fddb534/c.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221102200838/http://xinhuanet.com/tech/20221101/a16de507cf514c6283c75e2e9fddb534/c.html |archive-date=2 November 2022 |access-date=3 November 2022 |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]]}}</ref><ref name="nsf_mengtian2" /> ''Mengtian'' was launched and docked with ''Tianhe'' on 31 October 2022<ref name="abc_mengtian" /> and moved to its permanent port-side position on 3 November.<ref name=":1" />

Together, the two experiment modules support microgravity and freefall research that cannot be conducted on Earth for extended periods. Experiments can also be mounted externally for exposure to the [[space environment]], including cosmic radiation, vacuum, and the [[solar wind]].<ref name="abc_mengtian" /> ''Wentian'' focuses primarily on life sciences, while ''Mengtian'' is oriented toward microgravity research.<ref name="xinhua_mengtian" />

Both experiment modumes are equipped with rendezvous hardware for automated docking to the forward port of ''Tianhe''. After docking and inspections, the indexing robotic arms mounted on ''Wentian'' and ''Mengtian''—similar in function to the [[Lyappa arm]] used on ''Mir''—were used to relocate ''Wentian'' to the starboard port and ''Mengtian'' to the port-side port.<ref name="indexarm">{{cite news |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2021/04/china-station-construction-begins/ |title=China readies launch of Tianhe module, the start of ambitious two-year station construction effort |first1=William |last1=Graham |first2=Chris |last2=Gebhardt |date=28 April 2021 |website=NASASpaceflight.com |access-date=22 June 2021 |archive-date=19 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210519145548/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2021/04/china-station-construction-begins/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The CMM on ''Tianhe'' can also serve as a backup for module relocation.<ref name="indexarm_yang">{{Cite book |first=Hong |last=Yang |title=Manned Spacecraft Technologies |publisher=Springer |year=2020 |isbn=978-9811548970 |location=China |pages=355}}</ref><ref name="indexarm" />

