=== Systems ===
==== Communication ====
Real-time communications, including live audio and video links, are provided by the [[Tianlian#Tianlian II|Tianlian II]] series of data relay satellites. A [[Satellite constellation|constellation]] of three satellites was launched into [[geostationary orbit]]s, providing communication and data support for the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-communications-satellite-tiangong-space-station |title=China launches new communications satellite to support Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=14 July 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=21 July 2022 |archive-date=21 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220721081331/https://www.space.com/china-launches-communications-satellite-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Docking ====
Tiangong is equipped with the [[Chinese Docking Mechanism]], first used by Shenzhou 8 spacecraft and the Tiangong-1 space laboratory.<ref>{{cite web |date=27 April 2004 |title=Testimony of James Oberg: Senate Science, Technology, and Space Hearing: International Space Exploration Program |url=http://www.spaceref.com/news/viewsr.html?pid=12687 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910032342/http://www.spaceref.com/news/viewsr.html?pid=12687 |archive-date=10 September 2012 |access-date=1 February 2012 |publisher=SpaceRef}}</ref><ref name="Jam">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Morris |date=18 November 2011 |title=Shenzhou for Dummies |url=http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Shenzhou_for_Dummies_999.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211019090104/https://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Shenzhou_for_Dummies_999.html |archive-date=19 October 2021 |access-date=1 February 2012 |work=SpaceDaily}}</ref> This system is based on the [[Androgynous Peripheral Attach System|APAS-89/APAS-95]] developed by Russia and NASA. While NASA has described it as a "clone" of APAS,<ref name="her">{{cite conference |author1=John Cook |author2=Valery Aksamentov |author3=Thomas Hoffman |author4=Wes Bruner |date=1 January 2011 |title=ISS Interface Mechanisms and their Heritage |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20110010964.pdf |conference=AIAA Space 2011 (Long Beach, CA) |page=26 |id=JSC-CN-24225 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220425215929/https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20110010964.pdf |archive-date=25 April 2022 |access-date=31 March 2015 |quote=The Chinese APAS is a clone of the Russian APAS. A view of the Chinese APAS is shown in Figure 19 |via=NTRS – NASA Technical Reports Server |url-status=live}}</ref> there are conflicting claims about its compatibility with current and future docking mechanisms on the ISS, which are also APAS-based.<ref name="Jam" /><ref>{{cite news |date=1 August 2011 |title=China's First Space Station Module Readies for Liftoff |url=http://www.spacenews.com/civil/110801-china-space-station-module-readies.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120917201507/http://www.spacenews.com/civil/110801-china-space-station-module-readies.html |archive-date=17 September 2012 |access-date=18 June 2021 |publisher=SpaceNews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Go Taikonauts Team |date=9 September 2011 |title=Chinese Docking Adapter Compatible with International Standard |url=http://www.go-taikonauts.com/en/chinese-space-news/211-chinese-docking-adapter-compatible-with-international-standard |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605010943/http://www.go-taikonauts.com/en/chinese-space-news/211-chinese-docking-adapter-compatible-with-international-standard |archive-date=5 June 2022 |access-date=1 February 2012 |publisher=Go Taikonaut}}</ref> The mechanism features a circular transfer passage with a diameter of {{Convert|800|mm}}.<ref>{{cite web |date=31 October 2011 |title=Differences between Shenzhou-8 and Shenzhou-7 |url=http://english.cntv.cn/special/tiangong1/20111031/114506.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328155831/http://english.cntv.cn/special/tiangong1/20111031/114506.shtml |archive-date=28 March 2016 |access-date=17 March 2015 |publisher=CCTV |quote=there will be an 800-millimetre cylindrical passage connecting Shenzhou-8 and Tiangong-1.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=18 June 2012 |title=Chinese astronauts open door on orbiting research lab |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/china/shenzhou9/120618docking/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211019104036/https://spaceflightnow.com/china/shenzhou9/120618docking/ |archive-date=19 October 2021 |access-date=17 March 2015 |website=Spaceflight Now |quote=Jing floated through the narrow 31-inch passage leading into Tiangong 1}}</ref> The androgynous variant weighs {{Convert|310|kg|abbr=on}}, while the non-androgynous version weighs {{Convert|200|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Qiu Huayon |author2=Liu Zhi|author3=Shi Junwei|author4=Zheng Yunqing|date=August 2015|page=12|title=Birth of the Chinese Docking System|magazine=Go Taikonauts!|issue=16}}</ref>

==== Power supply ====
[[File:Tianhe solar array deployment.gif|thumb|160px|alt=Deployment of flexible solar arrays on Tianhe core module|Animation showing the deployment of flexible solar arrays on the [[Tianhe core module]]]]
[[Electrical power]] is provided by two steerable flexible [[Photovoltaic system|solar arrays]] on each module, using [[Gallium arsenide#Solar cells and detectors|gallium arsenide]] [[photovoltaic]] cells to convert sunlight into electricity. Energy is stored for use when the station passes through Earth’s shadow. Resupply spacecraft replenish fuel for propulsion engines, which maintain orbit and counter atmospheric drag. The solar arrays are designed to last up to 15 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-06/09/c_139999119.htm |title=China Focus: Effective power supply energizes China's space station project |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=9 June 2021 |access-date=11 June 2021 |archive-date=9 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210609173932/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-06/09/c_139999119.htm |url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Propulsion and attitude control ====
Tiangong uses conventional [[Rocket engine|chemical engines]] and [[ion thruster]]s for orbital adjustments and station-keeping.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Wang |first=Xiang |last2=Zhang |first2=Qiao |last3=Wang |first3=Wei |date=January 2023 |title=Design and Application Prospect of China’s Tiangong Space Station |url=https://spj.science.org/doi/10.34133/space.0035 |journal=Space: Science & Technology |language=en |volume=3 |doi=10.34133/space.0035 |issn=2692-7659}}</ref>

The Tianhe core module is equipped with four [[Hall-effect thruster]]s, the first ever used on a crewed spacecraft.<ref>{{cite web |last=Zhang |first=Baoshu |date=21 June 2021 |title=配置4台霍尔电推进发动机 "天宫"掀起太空动力变革 |trans-title=Equipped with four Hall-effect electric propulsion engines, "Tiangong" is spearheading a revolution in space propulsion. |url=http://www.chinanews.com/gn/2021/06-21/9503717.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210706020905/http://www.chinanews.com/gn/2021/06-21/9503717.shtml |archive-date=6 July 2021 |accessdate=18 July 2021 |website=China News Network |language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://interestingengineering.com/science/chinas-new-space-station-will-be-powered-by-ion-propulsion-system |title=China's New Space Station Will Be Powered by Ion Propulsion System |website=Interesting Engineering |date=3 June 2021 |first=Derya |last=Ozdemir |access-date=8 October 2022 |archive-date=8 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221008222249/https://interestingengineering.com/science/chinas-new-space-station-will-be-powered-by-ion-propulsion-system |url-status=live}}</ref> These thrusters are far more efficient than traditional engines, cutting fuel use by 90%. Ground tests showed the system can run for more than 8,000 hours without failure, supporting Tiangong’s planned 15-year lifespan. Magnetic shielding and advanced ceramics protect the engines and module from erosion caused by high-speed ion particles.<ref name="Chen-2021">{{cite news |last=Chen |first=Stephen |date=2 June 2021 |title=How China's space station could help power astronauts to Mars |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3135770/how-chinas-space-station-could-help-power-astronauts-mars |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210622194931/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3135770/how-chinas-space-station-could-help-power-astronauts-mars |archive-date=22 June 2021 |access-date=22 June 2021 |work=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref>

For attitude control, Tiangong relies mainly on 12 [[control moment gyroscope]]s, which allow precise orientation without burning fuel, saving propellant and extending the station’s life. They provide high pointing accuracy—better than 0.1°—for Earth observation and scientific experiments. This system also keeps the station stable during reboost maneuvers by visiting cargo ships.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Wang |first1=Xiang |last2=Zhang |first2=Qiao |last3=Wang |first3=Wei |date=January 2023 |title=Design and Application Prospect of China's Tiangong Space Station |journal=Space: Science & Technology |language=en |volume=3 |article-number=0035 |doi=10.34133/space.0035 |bibcode=2023SpScT...3...35W |issn=2692-7659|doi-access=free }}</ref>

==== Robotic arms ====
[[File:Combined robotic arm of Tiangong.jpg|thumb|alt=15 m combined robotic arm on Tiangong|The combined CMM and EMM arms]]
The Tiangong space station features three robotic arms. The largest is a {{Convert|10|m|4=-long|adj=mid}} arm called the Core Module Manipulator (CMM) mounted on the ''Tianhe'' core module. Its function is similar to the [[Canadarm2]] on the International Space Station.<ref name="s12_arm" />

The ''Wentian'' module is equipped with a {{Convert|5|m|4=-long|adj=mid}} arm called the Experiment Module Arm (EMM) that is five times more precise in positioning than the CMM. This arm is primarily used to transfer experiments and other hardware outside the station during astronaut EVAs<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Fallahiarezoodar|first=Nasim|last2=Zhu|first2=Zheng H.|date=2 July 2025|title=Review of Autonomous Space Robotic Manipulators for On-Orbit Servicing and Active Debris Removal|url=https://spj.science.org/doi/10.34133/space.0291|journal=Space: Science & Technology|language=en|volume=5|doi=10.34133/space.0291|issn=2692-7659|doi-access=free}}</ref>. A dual-arm connector on CMM allows it to link with the ''Wentian'' arm, extending its reach and increasing its weight-handling capacity.<ref name="s13_spacewalk" />

The ''Mengtian'' module carries a payload release mechanism designed to assist with experiment transfers.<ref name="xinhua_mengtian" /><ref name="nsf_mengtian" /> This robotic arm can retrieve experiments from the cargo airlock and install them onto the module’s exterior.<ref name="scmp_mengtian_2" /> It can also be used to deploy [[Small satellite|microsatellites]].<ref name="nsf_mengtian" /><ref name="cbs_mengtian">{{cite web |date=31 October 2022 |title=China launches lab module Mengtian as space station approaches completion |url=http://www.china.org.cn/china/2022-10/31/content_78494902.htm |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221101035612/http://www.china.org.cn/china/2022-10/31/content_78494902.htm |archive-date=1 November 2022 |access-date=3 November 2022 |website=China News Service}}</ref>

Additionally, there are two indexing robotic arms installed near the docking ports of the two laboratory modules. These arms were used to relocate the modules from their initial docking port to their final positions, similar in function to the [[Lyappa arm]] on the ''Mir'' space station.<ref name="indexarm" /><ref name="indexarm_yang" /><ref>{{cite web |title=中国空间站成功完成"太空泊车"，上海航天专家揭秘背后高科技 |url=https://finance.sina.com.cn/tech/discovery/2022-10-01/doc-imqmmtha9481311.shtml?finpagefr=p_114 |language=Chinese |website=新浪科技  |date=30 September 2022 |archive-date=2 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221102033156/https://finance.sina.com.cn/tech/discovery/2022-10-01/doc-imqmmtha9481311.shtml?finpagefr=p_114 }}</ref>

=== Co-orbital space telescope ===
[[File:Xuntian Space Telescope mockup at NMC 01.jpg|thumb|''Xuntian'' mockup, showing its 2-meter diameter telescope]]

The ''[[Xuntian]]'' or Chinese space station survey telescope<ref>{{cite web |title=CSST科学工作委员会2026年度第一次会议在国家天文台召开|url=http://groups.bao.ac.cn/csst_jc/xsdt/202604/t20260416_830900.html|website=[[National Astronomical Observatories of China]]}}</ref> (CSST) is a [[space telescope]] under development.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gao|first1=Ming|last2=Zhao|first2=Guangheng|last3=Gu|first3=Yidong|url=http://www.bulletin.cas.cn/publish_article/2015/6/20150602.htm|title=我国空间站的空间科学与应用任务|trans-title=Space Science and Application Mission in China's Space Station|volume=30|issue=6|pages=721–732|journal=Bulletin of Chinese Academy of Sciences|publisher=[[Chinese Academy of Sciences|CAS]]|date=2015|access-date=2 May 2016|doi=10.16418/j.issn.1000-3045.2015.06.002|language=zh|archive-date=7 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211007194618/http://www.bulletin.cas.cn/publish_article/2015/6/20150602.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="cas-20220507">{{cite web |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/china-delays-launch-of-its-xuntian-space-telescope/|title=China Delays Launch of Its Xuntian Space Telescope|website=[[Scientific American]]|date=21 November 2023|access-date=11 March 2024}}</ref>

The telescope will feature a {{Convert|2|m|ftin|adj=on}} diameter [[primary mirror]] and is expected to have a field of view approximately 300 to 350 times larger than that of the [[Hubble Space Telescope]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurasiantimes.com/china-claims-its-xuntian-telescope-with-350-fold-bigger/|title=Outgunning NASA's Hubble, China Claims Its Xuntian Telescope with 350-Fold Bigger View Can Unravel 'Cosmic Mysteries'|date=8 May 2022}}</ref> Its 2.5-[[Gigapixel image|gigapixel]] camera is designed to survey up to 40 percent of the sky over it's minimum ten year service life.

As of 2026, ''Xuntian'' is scheduled for launch in 2027 aboard a [[Long March 5B]] rocket.<ref name="Jones 2026">{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Andrew |date=19 January 2026 |title=China previews how powerful its new Xuntian space telescope will be ahead of 2027 launch |url=https://www.space.com/astronomy/china-previews-how-powerful-its-new-xuntian-space-telescope-will-be-ahead-of-2027-launch-video |access-date=1 June 2026 |website=Space.com |language=en}}</ref> It is planned to [[Co-orbital configuration|co-orbit]] with the station, allowing periodic docking for servicing and maintenance.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones|first=Andrew|url=https://www.space.com/china-hubble-class-telescope-for-space-station|title=China wants to launch its own Hubble-class telescope as part of space station|work=[[Space.com]]|date=20 April 2021|access-date=22 April 2021}}</ref><ref name="Young 2022" />

== Construction ==
=== Planning ===
In 2011, it was announced that the future space station was planned to be assembled from 2020 to 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/11048-china-space-station-plans-details.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210621210805/https://www.space.com/11048-china-space-station-plans-details.html|url-status=dead|title=China Details Ambitious Space Station Goals|author1=Leonard David|date=7 March 2011|archivedate=21 June 2021|website=Space.com}}</ref> By 2013, the space station's core module was planned to be launched earlier, in 2018, followed by the first laboratory module in 2020, and a second in 2022.<ref name="Klotz">{{cite news |title=China Unveils Space Station Research Plans |first=Irene |last=Klotz
|url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/civil-space/38131china-unveils-space-station-research-plans |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131125024030/http://www.spacenews.com/article/civil-space/38131china-unveils-space-station-research-plans |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 November 2013 |newspaper=SpaceNews |date=12 November 2013 |access-date=16 November 2013}}</ref> By 2018, it was reported that this had slipped to 2020–2023.<ref name="ld20210421" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/chinese-space-program-insights-emerge-from-national-peoples-congress/|title=Chinese space program insights emerge from National People's Congress|date=2 April 2018|website=SpaceNews}}</ref> In February 2020, a total of 11 launches were planned for the whole construction phase, beginning in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Howell |first1=Elizabeth |title=China wants to build a new space station. A planned launch in April will set the stage. |url=https://www.space.com/china-space-station-april-launch-will-prepare.html |work=Space.com |language=en |access-date=16 October 2020 |archive-date=19 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201019225523/https://www.space.com/china-space-station-april-launch-will-prepare.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="sfn20210110" /> In 2021, it was reported China National Space Administration planned to complete the construction of the space station in 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2021/03/china-preparing-to-build-tiangong-station-in-2021-complete-by-2022/ |title=China preparing to build Tiangong station in 2021, complete by 2022 |website=NASASpaceFlight |date=1 March 2021 |first=Rui |last=C. Barbosa |access-date=2 March 2021 |archive-date=2 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210302021019/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2021/03/china-preparing-to-build-tiangong-station-in-2021-complete-by-2022/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

Tiangong modules are self-contained and pre-assembled, in contrast to the [[US Orbital Segment]] of the ISS, which required spacewalking to interconnect cables, piping, and structural elements manually. The assembly method of the station can be compared with the Soviet-Russian Mir space station and the Russian orbital segment of the International Space Station, making China the second nation to develop and use automatic rendezvous and docking for modular space station construction. The technologies in the construction are derived from decades of Chinese crewed spaceflight experiences, including those gained from [[Tiangong-1]] and [[Tiangong-2]] prototypes,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shine.cn/news/in-focus/2210201683/ |title=Spirit of space exploration motivates generations of Chinese astronauts |website=Shanghai Daily |date=20 October 2022 |first=Jian |last=Yang |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023040100/https://www.shine.cn/news/in-focus/2210201683/ |url-status=live}}</ref> as well as the purchase of aerospace technology from Russia in the early 1990s.<ref name="Futron-2003">{{cite web|url=http://www.futron.com/upload/wysiwyg/Resources/Whitepapers/China_n_%20Second_Space_Age_1003.pdf|title=China and the Second Space Age|access-date=6 October 2011|publisher=Futron Corporation|year=2003|author=Futron Corp.|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419165427/http://www.futron.com/upload/wysiwyg/Resources/Whitepapers/China_n_%20Second_Space_Age_1003.pdf|archive-date=19 April 2012}}</ref> A representative of the Chinese crewed space program stated that around 2000, China and Russia were engaged in technological exchanges regarding the development of a docking mechanism used for space stations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://russian.news.cn/dossiers/2011-11/03/c_131228371.htm|title=All components of the docking mechanism was designed and manufactured in-house China|date=3 November 2011|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |access-date=1 February 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426010439/http://russian.news.cn/dossiers/2011-11/03/c_131228371.htm|archive-date=26 April 2012}}</ref> Deputy Chief Designer, Huang Weifen, stated that near the end of 2009, CMSA began to train astronauts on how to dock spacecraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.qq.com/a/20111104/000142.htm|title=China next year manual spacecraft Temple docking, multiply group has completed primary|date=4 November 2011|newspaper=Beijing News|access-date=19 February 2012|archive-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718155858/http://news.qq.com/a/20111104/000142.htm|url-status=live}}</ref>

In accordance to the plan, by the end of 2022, the fully assembled Tiangong space station had three 22 metric-ton modules in a basic T-shape.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.popsci.com/science/tiangong-chinese-space-station/ |title=How Tiangong station will make China a force in the space race |website=Popular Science |date=8 September 2022 |first=Tatyana |last=Woodall |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=4 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221104123207/https://www.popsci.com/science/tiangong-chinese-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://time.com/6212281/china-tiangong-space-station-role/ |title=China's New Space Station Has a Big Role to Play—Scientifically and Diplomatically |magazine=TIME |date=12 September 2022 |first=Jeffrey |last=Kluger |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025012058/https://time.com/6212281/china-tiangong-space-station-role/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Because of the modular design, the Tiangong space station can be further expanded into six modules possibly enabling more astronaut participation in the future.<ref name="spacenews_modules" />

=== Assembly ===
[[File:Launch of Tianhe Core Module (Cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Long March 5B]] launching the [[Tianhe core module|''Tianhe'' core module]] in April 2021]]
[[File:CNEWS Wentian.png|thumb|Long March 5B launching the [[Wentian experiment module|''Wentian'' experiment module]] in July 2022]]
[[File:Module relocation with rotation arm on Tiangong.gif|thumb|alt=The module relocation process with rotation arm equipped by the Wentian module|Animation showing an "indexing robotic arm" relocating ''Wentian'' from the forward (top) to the starboard port of ''Tianhe'' (right)]]

The construction of the Chinese Space Station officially began in April 2021. The planned 11 missions include three module launches, four crewed missions, and four autonomous cargo flights.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-space-station-assembly-plans |title=China's new space station will need 10 more launches to complete |website=Space.com |date=30 April 2021 |first=Leonard |last=David |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=10 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220110064505/https://www.space.com/china-space-station-assembly-plans |url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 April 2021, the first component of the station, the ''Tianhe'' core module, was launched to orbit aboard the [[Long March 5B]] rocket from [[Wenchang Spacecraft Launch Site]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-core-module-tianhe-space-station |title=China launches core module of new space station to orbit |website=Space.com |date=29 April 2021 |first=Mike |last=Well |access-date=29 April 2021 |archive-date=28 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220928120340/https://www.space.com/china-launches-core-module-tianhe-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 May 2021, the [[Tianzhou 2]] autonomous cargo spacecraft was launched to the ''Tianhe'' core module in preparation for the [[Shenzhou 12]] crew, who will be responsible for testing ''Tianhe'''s various systems and preparing for future operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-tianzhou-2-cargo-mission-launch |title=China launches new cargo ship to Tianhe space station module |website=Space.com |date=29 May 2021 |first=Mike |last=Wall |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=26 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220626091356/https://www.space.com/china-tianzhou-2-cargo-mission-launch |url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 June 2021, Shenzhou 12 docked with the space station, marking them the first visitors to the Tiangong station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/shenzhou-12-docks-china-space-station-tianhe |title=China's Shenzhou 12 spacecraft docks at space station with 3 astronauts |website=Space.com |date=17 June 2021 |first=Mike |last=Well |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023032910/https://www.space.com/shenzhou-12-docks-china-space-station-tianhe |url-status=live}}</ref> The crew began the examination of the core module and verification of key technologies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-astronauts-space-station-tianhe-shenzhou-12 |title=China launches 3 astronauts to new space station |website=Space.com |date=17 June 2021 |first=Mike |last=Well |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023032855/https://www.space.com/china-launches-astronauts-space-station-tianhe-shenzhou-12 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 4 July 2021, [[Liu Boming (taikonaut)|Liu Boming]] and [[Tang Hongbo]] began their first spacewalk in upgraded Chinese [[Feitian space suit|Feitian spacesuits]], outfitting the space stations with [[extravehicular activity]] (EVA) equipment, such as foot restraints and a standing platform for the Core Module Manipulator (CMM). Shenzhou 12 commander [[Nie Haisheng]] stayed inside the station and tested the robotic arm movements.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-space-station-first-shenzhou-12-spacewalk |title=Chinese astronauts install tools on first spacewalk outside new space station |website=Space.com |date=4 July 2021 |first=Robert |last=Z. Pearlman |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=16 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220716144853/https://www.space.com/china-space-station-first-shenzhou-12-spacewalk |url-status=live}}</ref> Liu Boming and Nie Haisheng completed the second spacewalk on 20 August 2021 and installed various devices outside of the station, including a thermal control system, a panoramic camera, and other equipment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-space-station-2nd-spacewalk |title=Chinese astronauts complete second spacewalk at new space station |website=Space.com |date=20 August 2021 |first=Tereza |last=Pultarova |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=10 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220910002153/https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-space-station-2nd-spacewalk |url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 September 2021, the Shenzhou 12 crew entered their return spacecraft and undocked from ''Tianhe''. Before leaving the orbit, the crew performed various [[Space rendezvous#Methods of approach|radial rendezvous]] (R-Bar) maneuvers to circumnavigate around the space station. They tested the guidance system and recorded lighting conditions while approaching the ''Tianhe'' from different angles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2021/09/16/shenzhou-crew-departs-chinese-space-station-heads-for-earth/ |title=Shenzhou crew departs Chinese space station, heads for Earth |website=Spaceflight Now |date=16 September 2021 |first=Stephen |last=Clark |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220925141255/https://spaceflightnow.com/2021/09/16/shenzhou-crew-departs-chinese-space-station-heads-for-earth/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="s12_tz13">{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/china-rolls-out-cargo-mission-rocket-as-shenzhou-12-astronauts-leave-space-station/ |title=China rolls out cargo mission rocket as Shenzhou-12 astronauts leave space station |website=Space News |date=16 September 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref> The crew landed in the [[Gobi Desert]] of [[Inner Mongolia]] on the same day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-space-station-astronauts-shenzhou-12-landing-soon |title=China's 1st space station crew to return to Earth on Friday |website=Space.com |date=16 September 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025005430/https://www.space.com/china-space-station-astronauts-shenzhou-12-landing-soon |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Tianzhou 3]] cargo spacecraft, which arrived at the launch facility a month earlier,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/rocket-arrives-for-second-chinese-space-station-cargo-mission/ |title=Rocket arrives for second Chinese space station cargo mission |website=Space News |date=16 August 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref> was immediately rolled out onto the launch pad for the next supply mission.<ref name="s12_tz13" />

On 20 September 2021, the [[Tianzhou 3]] autonomous freighter was launched from the Wenchang Satellite Launch Center in preparation for the arrival of the [[Shenzhou 13]] crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-tianzhou-3-cargo-ship-launch |title=China launches Tianzhou 3 cargo ship to new space station |website=Space.com |date=20 September 2021 |first=Mike |last=Well |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023032911/https://www.space.com/china-tianzhou-3-cargo-ship-launch |url-status=live}}</ref> Shenzhou 13 was the first six-month mission on the Tiangong station, whereas Shenzhou 12 was only three months in length.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-readies-shenzhou-13-for-space-station-emergency |title=China is readying Shenzhou 13 spacecraft in case of space station emergency |website=Space.com |date=26 June 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023032852/https://www.space.com/china-readies-shenzhou-13-for-space-station-emergency |url-status=live}}</ref> The Shenzhou 13 spacecraft docked with the space station on 15 October 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-shenzhou-13-astronauts-to-space-station |title=China launches Shenzhou 13 astronauts on historic mission to new space station |website=Space.com |date=15 October 2021 |first=Mike |last=Wall |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=15 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211015171544/https://www.space.com/china-launches-shenzhou-13-astronauts-to-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/10/16/chinese-astronauts-arrive-at-space-station-for-longest-mission |title=China's Shenzhou-13 docks at space station for longest mission |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=16 October 2021 |author=AFP |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023035736/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/10/16/chinese-astronauts-arrive-at-space-station-for-longest-mission |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/china-international-space-station-beijing-foreign-ministry-mars-b1939537.html |title=China's Shenzhou-13 spacecraft docks for 6-month mission |website=Independent |date=16 October 2021 |author=AP |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023035739/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/china-international-space-station-beijing-foreign-ministry-mars-b1939537.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Missions for the Shenzhou 13 crew included orbit experiments, spacewalks, and for the station's future expansion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2022/04/15/chinese-astronauts-undock-from-space-station-head-for-landing/ |title=Chinese astronauts undock from space station, head for landing |website=Spaceflight Now |date=15 April 2022 |first=Stephen |last=Clark |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=5 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221005190912/https://spaceflightnow.com/2022/04/15/chinese-astronauts-undock-from-space-station-head-for-landing/ |url-status=live}}</ref> On 7 November 2021, Shenzhou 13 crew [[Zhai Zhigang]] and [[Wang Yaping]] conducted the first spacewalks to test the next-generation EVA suit and the CMM, making Wang Yaping China's first female spacewalker.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-first-female-spacewalk |title=China's Shenzhou 13 crew takes its first spacewalk, the country's 1st by a female astronaut |website=Space.com |date=7 November 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=7 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211107191224/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-first-female-spacewalk |url-status=live}}</ref> One of the missions in the 6.5-hour extravehicular activity was to install a dual-arm connector to the {{convert|10|m|ft|adj=mid|-long}} robotic arm, providing the capability for CMM to extend in length with another {{convert|5|m|ft|adj=mid|-long}} segment mounted on the ''Wentian'' module. According to Gao Shen of the [[China Academy of Space Technology]] (CAST), the combined {{convert|15|m|ft|adj=on}} CMM will have greater range and weight-carrying capacity.<ref name="s13_spacewalk">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-spacewalk-shenzhou-13 |title=China's first Shenzhou 13 spacewalk sees 2 astronauts test suits, robotic arm |website=Space.com |date=11 November 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=19 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220219153354/https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-spacewalk-shenzhou-13 |url-status=live}}</ref> During spacewalks, various preparations were performed on the robotic arm for manipulation and construction of future modules.<ref name="s13_spacewalk" />

On 26 December 2021, Shenzhou 13 crew Zhai Zhigang and [[Ye Guangfu]] conducted the second spacewalk to install a panoramic camera, which will be used for space station monitoring and robotic arm observation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-second-spacewalk-shenzhou |title=Spacewalking Chinese astronauts add camera to Tiangong space station module |website=space.com |date=28 December 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023035736/https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-second-spacewalk-shenzhou |url-status=live}}</ref> They also practiced various movements with the help of the CMM controlled by monitoring astronaut Wang Yaping inside the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2021/12/shenzhou-13-second-spacewalk/ |title=Shenzhou-13 crew conducts second spacewalk of mission |website=NASASpaceFlight |date=26 December 2021 |first=Justin |last=Davenport |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=27 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211227004513/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2021/12/shenzhou-13-second-spacewalk/ |url-status=live}}</ref> During the construction phase of the station in 2021, according to documents filed by [[China Manned Space Agency]] (CMSA) with the [[United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs]] and reported by Reuters, the station had two "close encounters" with [[SpaceX]]'s [[Starlink]] satellites on 1 July and 21 October, with the station conducting evasive adjustment maneuvers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2021/dec/28/china-complains-to-un-after-space-station-is-forced-to-move-to-avoid-starlink-satellites |title=China berates US after 'close encounters' with Elon Musk satellites |website=The Guardian |date=28 December 2021 |first=Jon |last=Henley |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025005422/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2021/dec/28/china-complains-to-un-after-space-station-is-forced-to-move-to-avoid-starlink-satellites |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/china/chinese-citizens-slam-musk-online-after-space-station-near-misses-2021-12-27/|title=Chinese citizens slam Musk online after space station near-misses |work=Reuters |date=27 December 2021 |access-date=9 January 2022 |archive-date=24 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220124071623/https://news.trust.org/item/20211227104501-7yl24 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3166290/spacex-satellites-encounters-chinese-space-station-were-not |title=SpaceX satellites' encounters with Chinese space station were not emergencies, US says |website=South China Morning Post |date=8 February 2022 |last=Liu |first=Zhen |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025005423/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3166290/spacex-satellites-encounters-chinese-space-station-were-not |url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 January 2022, Shenzhou 13 team used the 10-meter long CMM to relocate the [[Tianzhou 2]] supply ship by 20 degrees before returning it to the original location. This maneuver was conducted to practice the procedures, equipment, and backup operation system needed for future module assembly.<ref name="s12_arm">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-space-station-robotic-arm-construction-test |title=On China's new space station, a robotic arm test paves way for future construction |website=Space.com |date=9 January 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023022946/https://www.space.com/china-space-station-robotic-arm-construction-test |url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 January, the crew tested the emergency docking system by controlling the cargo spacecraft manually.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-emergency-docking-test |title=China's Shenzhou 13 astronauts manually fly cargo ship for emergency docking test |website=Space.com |date=13 January 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023035736/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-emergency-docking-test |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2022, the crew began preparations to undock from the space station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-crew-april-return-earth |title=China's record-setting Shenzhou 13 crew preparing for mid-April return to Earth |website=Space.com |date=30 March 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023035738/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-crew-april-return-earth |url-status=live}}</ref> The crew landed in China on 16 April 2022, after staying 182 days in low-Earth orbit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-astronauts-landing-returns-to-earth |title=China's Shenzhou 13 capsule lands with crew of 3 after record-setting mission |website=Space.com |date=16 April 2022 |first=Mike |last=Wall |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=16 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220416102103/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-13-astronauts-landing-returns-to-earth |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/shenzhou-13-astronauts-return-to-earth-after-182-day-mission/ |title=Shenzhou-13 astronauts return to Earth after 182-day mission |website=Space News |date=16 April 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref> Soon after, China launched the [[Tianzhou 4]] cargo spacecraft in preparation for the next crewed mission in May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/05/tianzhou-4-launch/ |title=Tianzhou 4 cargo launch to begin busy space station year for China |website=NASA Space Flight |date=9 May 2022 |first=Adrian |last=Beil |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023035737/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/05/tianzhou-4-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The automated freighter docked with the space station on 9 May 2022, and carried vital maintenance equipment and a refrigerator for scientific experiment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/tianzhou-4-cargo-craft-docks-with-chinese-space-station/ |title=Tianzhou-4 cargo craft docks with Chinese space station |website=Space News |date=9 May 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref>

[[File:Shenzhou-13 spacewalk.jpg|thumb|[[Zhai Zhigang]] of the [[Shenzhou 13]] crew conducting a [[spacewalk]] outside the station on 7 November 2021]]
[[File:Mengtian launch.jpg|thumb|Long March 5B launching the [[Mengtian experiment module|''Mengtian'' experiment module]] in October 2022]]

Beginning with [[Shenzhou 14]], China officially started the final construction phase for the space station, with three astronauts tasked to oversee the arrival of two laboratory modules in 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-14-mission-launch-success |title=China launches 3 astronauts to oversee construction of new Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=5 June 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=5 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605094810/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-14-mission-launch-success |url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 June 2022, the Shenzhou 14 crew arrived at the space station,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-14-mission-arrives-tiangong-space-station |title=3 Chinese astronauts arrive at Tiangong space station for 6-month stay |website=Space News |date=5 June 2022 |first=Mike |last=Will |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023032908/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-14-mission-arrives-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref> docking at the Earth-facing nadir port.<ref name="s14_docking" /> The Shenzhou 14 crew began the assembly for both the ''Wentian'' and ''Mengtian'' modules, which arrived in the second half of 2022.<ref name="s14_docking">{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/shenzhou-14-crewed-mission-arrives-at-chinese-space-station/ |title=Shenzhou-14 crewed mission arrives at Chinese space station |website=Space News |date=5 June 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref> The crew installed a carbon dioxide reduction system for the space station, tested their Feitian spacesuits, and debugged the ''Tianhe'' core module.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-14-astronauts-one-month-orbit |title=China's Shenzhou 14 astronauts mark busy 1st month aboard Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=9 July 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025005425/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-14-astronauts-one-month-orbit |url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 July 2022, [[Tianzhou 3]] was undocked from the station, making way for the arrival of the ''Wentian'' module.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/tianzhou-3-cargo-ship-undocks-tiangong-station |title=Tianzhou 3 cargo ship undocks from China's Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=19 July 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=19 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221119150058/https://www.space.com/tianzhou-3-cargo-ship-undocks-tiangong-station |url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 July 2022, the ''Wentian'' laboratory module was launched from the [[Wenchang Space Launch Site|Wenchang space centre]] and rendezvoused with the ''Tianhe'' core module on the same day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/07/wentian-launch/ |title=Chang Zheng 5B launches Wentian Laboratory Module |website=NASA Spaceflight |date=24 July 2022 |first=Adrian |last=Beil |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025005425/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/07/wentian-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="s14_wentian">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-space-station-module-wentian |title=China launches 2nd space station module to support science experiments |website=Space.com |date=24 July 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=25 July 2022 |archive-date=24 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220724092237/https://www.space.com/china-launches-space-station-module-wentian |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Wentian'' is the second module for the Tiangong space station, and the first laboratory cabin module (LCM). The module is equipped with an [[airlock]] cabin, which will become the primary entry-exit point for future EVAs.<ref name="wt_airlock" /> The module also features backup avionics, propulsion, and life support systems, improving the Tiangong space station's [[Redundancy (engineering)|operational redundancy]].<ref name="s14_wentian" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/second-module-docks-at-chinas-space-station-large-rocket-stage-tracked-in-orbit/ |title=Second module docks at China's space station, large rocket stage tracked in orbit |website=Space News |date=24 July 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref> On 2 September 2022, crew members [[Chen Dong (taikonaut)|Chen Dong]] and [[Liu Yang (taikonaut)|Liu Yang]] performed their first spacewalk from the new ''Wentian'' airlock, installing and adjusting various external equipment as well as testing emergency return procedures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://phys.org/news/2022-09-china-shenzhou-astronauts-spacewalk.html |title=China's Shenzhou-14 astronauts carry out spacewalk |website=Phys.org |date=2 September 2022 |author=AFP |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025005423/https://phys.org/news/2022-09-china-shenzhou-astronauts-spacewalk.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="s14_wt_2">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-spacewalk-from-new-module |title=China's Shenzhou 14 astronauts perform 1st spacewalk out of new module (video) |website=Space.com |date=2 September 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=13 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220913051850/https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-spacewalk-from-new-module |url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 September 2022, astronauts Chen Dong and [[Cai Xuzhe]] performed the mission's second spacewalk, installing external pumps and verified emergency rescue capability.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/chinese-astronauts-tiangong-space-station-wentian-spacewalk-september-2022 |title=Chinese astronauts take 4-hour spacewalk outside new lab at Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=17 September 2022 |first=Elizabeth |last=Howell |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=10 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221010175501/https://www.space.com/chinese-astronauts-tiangong-space-station-wentian-spacewalk-september-2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 30 September 2022, all crew members worked in coordination, moving the ''Wentian'' module from the forward port to the starboard lateral docking port, its planned permanent location, on 30 September 2022 at 04:44 UTC.<ref>{{cite web |title=我国成功实施问天实验舱转位 |url=https://news.sciencenet.cn/htmlnews/2022/9/487156.shtm |publisher=科学新闻网 |language=Chinese |date=30 September 2022 |access-date=30 September 2022 |archive-date=30 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220930055348/https://news.sciencenet.cn//htmlnews/2022/9/487156.shtm |url-status=live}}</ref> The relocation process was largely automated with the assistance of the indexing robotic arm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-moves-module-tiangong-space-station-video |title=China moves Tiangong space station module to side docking port (video) |website=Space.com |date=7 October 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=8 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221008135236/https://www.space.com/china-moves-module-tiangong-space-station-video |url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2022, CMSA prepared to launch the third and final module, ''[[Mengtian]]'', to complete the construction for the Tiangong space station.<ref name="spacenews_modules">{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/china-gears-up-for-launches-to-complete-tiangong-space-station/ |title=China gears up for launches to complete Tiangong space station |website=Space News |date=18 October 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-rocket-rollout-launch-mengtian-space-station-module |title=China rolls out rocket to launch 3rd and final space station module (photos) |website=Space.com |date=26 October 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=31 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031194231/https://www.space.com/china-rocket-rollout-launch-mengtian-space-station-module |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 31 October 2022, the ''Mengtian'' module was launched from the Wenchang space centre,<ref name="scmp_mengtian_1">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3197851/china-launches-mengtian-sending-final-research-module-finish-construction-tiangong-space-station |title=China launches Mengtian research module to finish construction of Tiangong space station |website=South China Morning Post |date=31 October 2022 |last=Ling |first=Xin |access-date=5 November 2022 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105173421/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3197851/china-launches-mengtian-sending-final-research-module-finish-construction-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref> and docked with the station 13 hours later.<ref name="abc_mengtian" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/science/china-launches-final-space-station-module-mengtian-state-media-2022-10-31/ |title='Dreaming of the Heavens': China launches final module to space station |website=Reuters |date=31 October 2022 |first1=Ryan |last1=Woo |first2=Liangping |last2=Gao |access-date=31 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031225307/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/science/china-launches-final-space-station-module-mengtian-state-media-2022-10-31/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="sn_mengtian_dock">{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/final-module-docks-at-chinas-tiangong-space-station/ |title=Final module docks at China's Tiangong space station |website=SpaceNews |date=31 October 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=31 October 2022 |archive-date=16 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230116232141/https://spacenews.com/final-module-docks-at-chinas-tiangong-space-station/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The assembly of the ''Mengtian'' marked the final step in the 1.5-year construction process.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.wired.com/story/china-is-now-a-major-space-power-tiangong-space-station/ |title=China Is Now a Major Space Power |magazine=WIRED |date=4 November 2022 |first=Ramin |last=Skibba |access-date=4 November 2022 |archive-date=4 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221104120512/https://www.wired.com/story/china-is-now-a-major-space-power-tiangong-space-station/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-mengtian-module-tiangong-space-station |title=China launches final module to complete Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=30 October 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=31 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031194440/https://www.space.com/china-launches-mengtian-module-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/31/world/asia/china-launch-space-station.html |title=China Launches Its Space Station's Third and Final Module |website=The New York Times |date=31 October 2022 |first=Keith |last=Bradsher |access-date=31 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031225307/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/31/world/asia/china-launch-space-station.html |url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[China Academy of Space Technology]], the rendezvous and docking process for ''Mengtian'' was conducted expeditiously, as the-then L-shaped Tiangong station consumed large amounts of energy to stay oriented in its asymmetrical arrangement.<ref name="scmp_mengtian_2">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3197961/chinas-space-station-takes-final-shape-arrival-mengtian-module |title=China's space station takes final shape with the arrival of Mengtian module |website=South China Morning Post |date=1 November 2022 |last=Ling |first=Xin |access-date=5 November 2022 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105173422/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3197961/chinas-space-station-takes-final-shape-arrival-mengtian-module |url-status=live}}</ref> On 3 November 2022, ''Mengtian'' was relocated autonomously from the forward docking port to the port-side lateral docking port via the indexing robotic arm, and successfully berthed at its planned permanent location with the ''Tianhe'' module at 01:32UTC (9:32[[Beijing Time|BJT]]), forming a T-shape.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ecns.cn/news/sci-tech/2022-11-04/detail-ihcfnqqi1676484.shtml |title=In-orbit assembly maneuver a success |website=China News Service |date=4 November 2022 |access-date=4 November 2022 |archive-date=4 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221104192645/https://www.ecns.cn/news/sci-tech/2022-11-04/detail-ihcfnqqi1676484.shtml |url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently, CMSA announced the construction of the Tiangong space station as officially complete.<ref name="scmp_complete" /> The designer of ''Mengtian'' module, Li Guangxing, explained that the space station was maneuvered to a special position, utilizing the Earth's gravity to help stabilize the docking process.<ref name="scmp_complete" /> At 07:12 UTC, the [[Shenzhou 14]] crew entered the ''Mengtian'' module.<ref name="scmp_complete">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3198266/china-astronauts-say-hello-completed-tiangong-space-station |title=China astronauts say hello from completed Tiangong space station |website=South China Morning Post |date=3 November 2022 |first=Xin |last=Ling |access-date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=3 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103110919/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3198266/china-astronauts-say-hello-completed-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="space_complete">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-completes-tiangong-space-station |title=China completes T-shaped Tiangong space station with new Mengtian module move |website=Space.com |date=5 November 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=5 November 2022 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105181607/https://www.space.com/china-completes-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 November 2022, the [[Tianzhou 4]] cargo spacecraft undocked from the Tiangong, and [[Tianzhou 5]] was prepared to launch on the same day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/tianzhou-4-undocks-china-tiangong-space-station |title=Tianzhou 4 cargo spacecraft undocks from China's Tiangong space station (video) |website=Space.com |date=10 November 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=12 November 2022 |archive-date=19 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221119151216/https://www.space.com/tianzhou-4-undocks-china-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref> Tianzhou 5 was launched on 12 November 2022, carrying supplies, experiments, and microsatellites to the space station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-launches-tianzhou-5-mission-tiangong-space-station |title=China launches Tianzhou 5 cargo ship to Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=12 November 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=12 November 2022 |archive-date=12 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112102153/https://www.space.com/china-launches-tianzhou-5-mission-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3199398/china-sends-cargo-space-station-resupply-next-manned-mission |title=China sends up cargo to space station to resupply for next manned mission |website=South China Morning Post |date=12 November 2022 |first=Josephine |last=Ma |access-date=12 November 2022 |archive-date=12 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112135207/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3199398/china-sends-cargo-space-station-resupply-next-manned-mission |url-status=live}}</ref> It also contained gifts for China's first crew handover ceremony in orbit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2329998-china-prepares-to-launch-laboratory-module-to-tiangong-space-station/ |title=China prepares to launch laboratory module to Tiangong space station |website=New Scientist |date=21 July 2022 |first=Alex |last=Wilkins |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025012040/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2329998-china-prepares-to-launch-laboratory-module-to-tiangong-space-station/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The completed station had extra capacity for expanded crew activities and living space for six, allowing crew rotation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3199338/china-prepares-weekend-mission-tiangong-space-station-stock-and-prepare-first-crew-handover-orbit |title=China prepares for [the] mission to Tiangong space station to stock up and prepare for first crew handover in orbit |website=South China Morning Post |date=11 November 2022 |first=Xin |last=Ling |access-date=14 November 2022 |archive-date=14 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221114030114/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3199338/china-prepares-weekend-mission-tiangong-space-station-stock-and-prepare-first-crew-handover-orbit |url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 November 2022, the [[Shenzhou 15]] crew, [[Fei Junlong]], [[Deng Qingming]], and [[Zhang Lu (taikonaut)|Zhang Lu]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/11/shenzhou-15-launch/ |title=China finishing busy Space station year with Shenzhou-15 |website=NASA spaceflight |date=29 November 2022 |first=Adrian |last=Beil |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=29 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221129175654/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/11/shenzhou-15-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref> were launched to the space station.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2022/11/29/china-space-station-crew-launch/ |title=China launches crew to recently completed space station |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=29 November 2022 |first=Christian |last=Davenport |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=1 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221201061251/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2022/11/29/china-space-station-crew-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The crew spent one week together for a handover and verifications for sustainable six-man operations.<ref name="Woo 2022">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/science/china-launches-crewed-spacecraft-chinese-space-station-state-television-2022-11-29/ |title=Chinese astronauts board space station in historic mission |website=Reuters |date=30 November 2022 |first1=Ryan |last1=Woo |first2=Liangping |last2=Gao |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=15 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221215110319/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/science/china-launches-crewed-spacecraft-chinese-space-station-state-television-2022-11-29/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="astronout_select">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-63798391 |title=Shenzhou-15: China sends new crew to Tiangong space station |publisher=BBC News |date=1 December 2022 |first1=Antoinette |last2=Radford |first2=Elsa |last1=Maishman |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=4 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221204011122/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-63798391 |url-status=live}}</ref> With the crew rotation operation, China commenced its permanent space presence.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/shenzhou-15-astronauts-arrive-at-chinas-space-station-for-first-crew-handover/ |title=Shenzhou 15 astronauts arrive at China's space station for first crew handover |website=Space News |date=29 November 2022 |first= Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2022/11/30/asia-pacific/china-space-us-military-pla/ |title=Chinese milestone sets stage for new space race with U.S. |website=The Japan Times |date=30 November 2022 |first=Gabriel |last=Dominguez |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=4 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221204011123/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2022/11/30/asia-pacific/china-space-us-military-pla/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-15-plans-tiangong-space-station |title=China's Shenzhou 15 crew has busy 6 months ahead aboard Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=3 December 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref>

On 17 December 2024, [[Cai Xuzhe]] broke the record with [[Song Lingdong]] for the longest spacewalk in human history, of 9 hours and 6 minutes, with the assistance of the space station's robotic arms and ground-based scientific personnel, completed tasks such as the installation of space debris protection devices, inspection, and maintenance of external equipment and facilities.<ref name="Jones 2024">{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Andrew |date=17 December 2024 |title=Shenzhou-19 astronauts complete record-breaking 9-hour spacewalk |url=https://spacenews.com/shenzhou-19-astronauts-complete-record-breaking-9-hour-spacewalk/ |access-date=18 December 2024 |website=SpaceNews |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Expansion ===
[[File:Tiangong expansion.jpg|thumb|alt=Possible future expansion of Tiangong space station|Possible future expansion of Tiangong space station]]
According to CMSA, the ''Tiangong'' space station is expected to be expanded from three to six modules,<ref name="scmp_mengtian_1" /><ref name="expansion">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-big-plans-tiangong-space-station |title=China lays out big plans for its new Tiangong space station |website=Space.com |date=3 May 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025005427/https://www.space.com/china-big-plans-tiangong-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref> with improved versions of the ''Tianhe'', ''Wentian'', and ''Mengtian'' modules.<ref name="expansion" />

According to Wang Xiang, commander of the space station system at the [[China Academy of Space Technology]] (CAST), the potential next phase would be adding a new core module. "Following our current design, we can continue to launch an extension module to dock with the forward section of the space station, and the extension module can carry a new hub for docking with the subsequent space vehicles," Wang told [[China Central Television|CCTV]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Andrew |date=7 December 2022 |title=China is considering expanding its Tiangong space station |url=https://spacenews.com/china-is-considering-expanding-its-tiangong-space-station/ |access-date=8 December 2022 |website=SpaceNews |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=杨书杰 |title=航天新征程｜中国空间站永远值得期待 |url=https://news.cctv.com/2022/12/05/ARTIhwEJuuLZxGCxOSM1YogV221205.shtml |access-date=8 December 2022 |website=news.cctv.com |archive-date=8 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221208025044/https://news.cctv.com/2022/12/05/ARTIhwEJuuLZxGCxOSM1YogV221205.shtml |url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2023, CAST presented new plan on the 74th [[International Astronautical Congress]] to expand the Tiangong to 180 tons, six-module assembly, with at least 15 years of operational life.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/space/china-double-size-space-station-touts-alternative-nasa-led-iss-2023-10-05/ |title=China to double size of space station, touts alternative to NASA-led ISS |work=Reuters |date=5 October 2023 |access-date=11 October 2023 |archive-date=11 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231011111720/https://www.reuters.com/technology/space/china-double-size-space-station-touts-alternative-nasa-led-iss-2023-10-05/ |url-status=live }}</ref> A multi-functional module with six docking ports was planned as the foundation for the expansion. New sections included [[3D printer]]s, robots, improved robotic arms, and space debris observation, detection, and warning systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spacenews.com/china-to-send-new-modules-and-co-orbiting-spacecraft-to-tiangong-space-station/ |title=China to send new modules and co-orbiting spacecraft to Tiangong space station |website=Space News |date=4 October 2023 |first=Andrew |last=Jones }}</ref>

The ''[[Xuntian]]'' space telescope, which will orbit independently of the station but is capable of docking with ''Tiangong'', is planned to launch in 2027.<ref name="Jones 2026" />

==International cooperation==
{{See also|Wolf Amendment|Politics of the International Space Station#China}}

After [[Shenzhou 5|''Shenzhou'' 5]], US commentators perceived an increase in China's chances of joining the [[International Space Station program]]. In 2007, China formally requested to join the International Space Station program.<ref name="ICAS">{{Cite web |title=Pursuing U.S.-China Cooperation in the Space Domain|url=https://chinaus-icas.org/research/pursuing-u-s-china-cooperation-in-the-space-domain/|access-date=25 April 2026|website=ICAS|language=en-US}}</ref> However, in 2011, the [[United States Congress|US Congress]] approved the [[Wolf Amendment]], which prohibits [[NASA]] from engaging in direct cooperation with Chinese space agencies, effectively excluding China from the International Space Station, incentivizing the [[Tiangong program|''Tiangong'' program]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Alamalhodaei |first=Aria |date=17 June 2021 |title=China launches 3 astronauts to its new space station core module |url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/06/17/china-launches-3-astronauts-to-its-new-space-station-core-module/?guccounter=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220513004715/https://techcrunch.com/2021/06/17/china-launches-3-astronauts-to-its-new-space-station-core-module/ |archive-date=13 May 2022 |access-date=29 June 2021 |website=TechCrunch}}</ref><ref name="ICAS" />

[[Roscosmos]], Russia's space agency, and the [[European Space Agency]] (ESA), two of NASA's ISS partners, expressed intentions to cooperate with China in space.<ref>{{cite web |date=27 October 2019 |title=Trouble in the Stars: The Importance of US-China Bilateral Cooperation in Space |url=https://hir.harvard.edu/trouble-in-the-stars-the-importance-of-us-china-bilateral-cooperation-in-space/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210615222717/https://hir.harvard.edu/trouble-in-the-stars-the-importance-of-us-china-bilateral-cooperation-in-space/ |archive-date=15 June 2021 |access-date=29 June 2021 |website=Harvard International Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=published|first=Tariq Malik|date=28 June 2010|title=China Has Not Been Invited to Join International Space Station, NASA Says|url=https://www.space.com/8675-china-invited-join-international-space-station-nasa.html|access-date=25 April 2026|website=Space|language=en}}</ref> Between 2007 and 2011, Russia, Europe, and China collaborated on the [[Mars500]] project, a ground-based simulation complementing ISS-based preparations for a [[human mission to Mars]].<ref name="Mars500 partners2">{{cite web |date=4 June 2011 |title=Mars500 partners |url=http://mars500.imbp.ru/en/partners.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027205156/http://mars500.imbp.ru/en/partners.html |archive-date=27 October 2012 |access-date=28 July 2022 |publisher=ESA}}</ref>

Tiangong hosts international experiments from 17 countries across 23 institutions, including Belgium, France, Germany, India, Italy, Japan, Mexico, the Netherlands, Peru, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Spain.<ref name="nature_un2">{{cite magazine |date=31 October 2022 |title=China's Space Ambitions Are Fueling Competition and Collaboration |url=https://time.com/6226631/china-space-station-mengtian-launch/ |magazine=TIME |access-date=31 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031225307/https://time.com/6226631/china-space-station-mengtian-launch/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs]] was involved in selecting nine of these international experiments.

[[File:Sea survival training China 382686.jpg|thumb|ESA and CMSA astronauts training together at the [[Astronaut Center of China]], on 14 August 2017]]

ESA began astronaut training with the China Manned Space Agency (CMSA) in 2017, preparing selected astronauts for potential Tiangong missions, including survival training, language instruction, and spacecraft operations.<ref>{{cite web |date=24 August 2017 |title=ESA and Chinese astronauts train together |url=https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Human_and_Robotic_Exploration/Astronauts/ESA_and_Chinese_astronauts_train_together |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210702073545/https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Human_and_Robotic_Exploration/Astronauts/ESA_and_Chinese_astronauts_train_together |archive-date=2 July 2021 |website=European Space Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=27 June 2018 |title=Why Europe's astronauts are learning Chinese |url=https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20180626-why-europes-astronauts-are-learning-chinese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221113155759/https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20180626-why-europes-astronauts-are-learning-chinese |archive-date=13 November 2022 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> In January 2023, ESA announced it would no longer send astronauts to Tiangong due to political and financial considerations.<ref name="Jones 2023">{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Andrew |date=25 January 2023 |title=ESA is no longer planning to send astronauts to China's Tiangong space station |url=https://spacenews.com/esa-is-no-longer-planning-to-send-astronauts-to-chinas-tiangong-space-station/ |publisher=Space News}}</ref>

Following the launch of Tiangong's first module in 2021, CMSA stated that multiple countries had expressed interest in sending astronauts to the station and that future foreign participation would be supported.<ref>{{cite news |last=Garcia |first=Carlos |date=17 June 2021 |title=Chinese astronauts board space station module in historic mission |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/china/china-launches-crewed-spacecraft-shenzhou-12-historic-mission-2021-06-17/ |website=Reuters}}</ref> Chinese officials have indicated that Chinese and foreign astronauts are expected to work together once the station is fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last=Amos |first=Jonathan |date=18 June 2021 |title=China space station: Shenzhou-12 delivers first crew to Tianhe module |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-57504052 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

In October 2022, CMSA opened astronaut selection to residents of [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]].<ref name="Woo 2022" /> As of late 2025, one astronaut from each region is expected to launch to ''Tiangong'' in 2026 as payload specialists.<ref name=":8" /> [[Lai Ka-ying]], a former [[Hong Kong Police Force]] officer, became the first [[Hong Kong resident]] to enter space, on 25 May 2026, flying aboard [[Shenzhou 23]].<ref name="BBC News 2026" />

In 2025, China and [[Pakistan]] signed an agreement to send a Pakistani astronaut to ''Tiangong'' on a short-duration mission.<ref>{{Cite news |title=China, for first time, to send foreign national Pakistani astronaut to its space station |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/china-for-first-time-to-send-foreign-national-pakistani-astronaut-to-its-space-station/articleshow/118631766.cms |access-date=1 March 2025 |work=The Times of India}}</ref> In April 2026, two [[Pakistan Air Force]] pilots were selected to begin training at the [[Astronaut Center of China]] in Beijing.<ref name="South China Morning Post 2026">{{Cite web |date=22 April 2026 |title=China names 2 Pakistani astronauts chosen to train for space station mission |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3351043/china-names-2-pakistani-astronauts-chosen-train-tiangong-space-station-mission |access-date=13 May 2026 |website=South China Morning Post |language=en}}</ref> One of these pilots is expected to launch aboard [[Shenzhou 24]] in October 2026 and visit the station for a week.<ref>{{Cite web |last=C |first=Jack |title=2026 Human Spaceflight Missions to Proceed as Planned Following 'Emergency Response' Mission |url=https://www.china-in-space.com/p/2026-human-spaceflight-missions-to |access-date=29 May 2026 |website=www.china-in-space.com |language=en}}</ref>

== Life aboard ==
=== Crew activities ===
{{See also|List of Tiangong space station spacewalks}}
[[File:Interior of Wentian.jpg|thumb|Interior of the [[Wentian module|Wentian lab module]]|alt=Interior of Wentian module at Tiangong Space Station]]

Astronauts on the Tiangong station follow [[China Standard Time]] (CST) for their daily schedule. The crew often wakes up around 7:00 and begins their daily conference with [[Beijing Aerospace Flight Control Center|Mission Control in Beijing]] before starting work at 08:00 (00:00UTC). The crew will then follow their planned schedule until 21:00, after which they report their work progress to Mission Control. At 13:30, astronauts enter their living quarters to take a [[nap]], which typically takes an hour. The crew also has multiple breaks for eating and resting.<ref name="bbc_life_tiangong">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-57593231 |title=中国空间站：第一次入住"天宫"的宇航员发布Vlog，他们在干什么 |website=BBC Chinese |date=24 June 2021 |author=BBC |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=25 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025220857/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-57593231 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Tiangong station features a lighting scene function to simulate lighting conditions on Earth, including daylight, dusk, and night. As the station experiences 16 sunrises and sunsets per day in [[low Earth orbit]], this function helps to avoid disruption to the crew's [[circadian rhythm]].<ref name="bbc_life_tiangong" /><ref name="xinhua_tiangong_life">{{cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-04/30/c_139917457.htm |title=Q&A: Getting to know China's space station |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=30 April 2021 |access-date=25 October 2022 |archive-date=26 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221026032119/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-04/30/c_139917457.htm |url-status=live}}</ref>

The Tiangong space station is fitted with [[home automation]] functions, including remote-controlled appliances and a logistics management system.<ref name="xinhua_tiangong_life" /> The crew can use their [[tablet computer]]s to identify, locate, and organize items inside the station, as all items in the station are marked by [[QR code]]s. This will help ensure an orderly environment as more cargo arrives.<ref name="xinhua_tiangong_life" /> Inter-device communication inside the station is completely wireless via the [[Wi-Fi]] network to avoid a [[cable management|cord mess]].<ref name="xinhua_tiangong_life" />

=== Food and personal hygiene ===
{{See also|Space food|Sleep in space}}
[[File:Space food for Chinese astronaut at NMC.jpg|thumb|Space food for Tiangong space station]]
Meals consisting of 120 different types of food, selected based on astronauts' preferences, are stored aboard. Staples including shredded pork in garlic sauce, [[kung pao chicken]], black pepper beef, [[yuxiang shredded pork]], pickled cabbage, and beverages, including a variety of teas and juices, are resupplied by trips of the [[Tianzhou (spacecraft)|Tianzhou-class]] robotic [[cargo spacecraft]]. Fresh fruit and vegetables are stored in coolers. Huang Weifen, the chief astronaut trainer of CMSA, explains that most of the food is prepared to be solid, boneless, and in small pieces. Condiments such as pork sauce and Sichuan pepper sauce are used to compensate for the changes in the sense of [[Effect of spaceflight on the human body#Taste|taste]] in microgravity. The station is equipped with a small kitchen table for food preparation, a refrigerator, a water dispenser, and the first-ever [[microwave oven]] in spaceflight<ref name="bbc_life_tiangong" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.21jingji.com/article/20210621/herald/6f5f6c26efbfe00d5d27457a84d1a739_zaker.html |title=神舟十二号里的"广东制造"：首台航天微波炉被送入太空，中国太空笔实现新突破 |website=21 jingji |language=Chinese |date=21 June 2021 |access-date=2 July 2021 |archive-date=9 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709182806/https://m.21jingji.com/article/20210621/herald/6f5f6c26efbfe00d5d27457a84d1a739_zaker.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://spacecentre.co.uk/blog-post/tiangong-space-station/ |title=Building the Tiangong Space Station |website=Space Centre |date=26 July 2022 |first=Dhara |last=Patel |access-date=24 October 2022 |archive-date=24 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221024000233/https://spacecentre.co.uk/blog-post/tiangong-space-station/ |url-status=live}}</ref> so that astronauts can "always have hot food whenever they need."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.space.com/china-astronauts-space-food-menu-shenzhou-12 |title=Chinese astronauts enjoying 120 dishes during space station stay |website=Space.com |date=26 June 2021|first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-space-station-life-panda-cartoon |title=Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Panda: Adorable cartoon shows astronaut life on Chinese space station |website=Space.com |date=28 June 2021 |first=Elizabeth |last=Howell |access-date=29 June 2021 |archive-date=29 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210629001832/https://www.space.com/china-space-station-life-panda-cartoon |url-status=live}}</ref> Following the astronauts' feedback, larger supplies of vegetables have been included since [[Tianzhou 4]], increasing the variety of vegetable to 32.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/tianzhou-4-cargo-craft-docks-with-chinese-space-station/ |title=Tianzhou-4 cargo craft docks with Chinese space station |website=Space News |date=10 May 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones}}</ref> Later, [[Shenzhou 21]] delivered an [[Convection oven#Air fryer|air fryer]] to the Tiangong, which features built-in air purification and residue collector to allow safe usage inside microgravity. The new oven allows [[baking]] and [[grilling]] of food, instead of simple reheating. Chinese astronauts cooked [[barbecue]] [[Chicken wings as food|chicken wings]] and grilled [[steak]] with it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.china-in-space.com/p/barbecue-feast-hosted-on-tiangong |title=Barbecue Feast Hosted on Tiangong During Crew Handover |website=China in Space |date=4 November 2025 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bastillepost.com/global/article/5338288-specially-designed-hot-air-oven-allows-chinese-astronauts-to-cook-in-orbit |title=Specially designed hot air oven allows Chinese astronauts to cook in orbit |website=Bastille Post |date=4 November 2025 }}</ref>

The station's core module, ''Tianhe,'' provides the living quarters for the crew members,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/yp/discover/news/asia/article/3131642/china-launches-tianhe-future-living-quarters-space-station |title=China launches Tianhe, future living quarters for space station planned for 2022 |agency=Reuters |website=scmp.com |date=29 April 2021 |access-date=5 October 2021 |archive-date=5 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211005120346/https://www.scmp.com/yp/discover/news/asia/article/3131642/china-launches-tianhe-future-living-quarters-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/04/29/china-launches-key-module-of-space-station-planned-for-2022-.html |title=China launches key module of space station planned for 2022, state media reports |website=CNBC |date=29 April 2021 |agency=Reuters |access-date=5 October 2021 |archive-date=5 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211005120346/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/04/29/china-launches-key-module-of-space-station-planned-for-2022-.html |url-status=live}}</ref> consisting of three separate sleeping berths,<ref name="Spaceflight Now 2021">{{cite web |title=Chinese astronauts enter Tiangong space station for first time |website=Spaceflight Now |date=17 June 2021 |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2021/06/17/chinese-astronauts-enter-tiangong-space-station-for-first-time/ |access-date=3 February 2022 |archive-date=17 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217131817/https://spaceflightnow.com/2021/06/17/chinese-astronauts-enter-tiangong-space-station-for-first-time/ |url-status=live}}</ref> a [[space toilet]], shower facility, and gym equipment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3137330/blast-chinas-shenzhou-12-manned-mission-build-space-station |title=First astronauts enter China's Tiangong space station after successful docking operation |website=scmp.com |date=17 June 2021 |first=Stephen |last=Chen |access-date=5 October 2021 |archive-date=5 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211005120356/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3137330/blast-chinas-shenzhou-12-manned-mission-build-space-station |url-status=live}}</ref> Each berth features one small circular window,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sohu.com/a/485024249_120399893 |title=贴心！原来天和核心舱有窗户，安装的位置人性化，一开始没猜出来 |website=Sohu News |date=22 August 2022 |language=Chinese |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=4 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221204215028/https://www.sohu.com/a/485024249_120399893 |url-status=live}}</ref> a headphone set, ventilation, and other amenities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-12-astronauts-earth-photos |title=China's Shenzhou 12 astronauts send back stunning images of Earth (photos) |website=Space.com |date=14 September 2021 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=23 October 2022 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023033030/https://www.space.com/china-shenzhou-12-astronauts-earth-photos |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Electrical muscle stimulation|Neuromuscular electrical stimulation]] is used to prevent muscle atrophy. The noise level in the working area is set at 58 decibels, while in the sleeping area, the noise is kept at 49 [[decibel]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://futurism.com/bunks-chinese-space-station-enormous |title=The Bunks in the Chinese Space Station Are Absolutely Enormous |website=Futurism |date=22 September 2021 |access-date=5 October 2021 |archive-date=5 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211005120346/https://futurism.com/bunks-chinese-space-station-enormous |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-06/17/c_1310014028.htm |title=China launches first crewed mission for space station construction |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=17 June 2021 |access-date=5 October 2021 |archive-date=19 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210619183311/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2021-06/17/c_1310014028.htm |url-status=live}}</ref> The ventilation system provides air circulation to the crew, with 0.08&nbsp;[[m/s]] wind speed for the working areas and 0.05&nbsp;m/s for the sleeping stations.<ref name="xinhua_tiangong_life" /> Three additional living quarters for short-term stay are located in the [[Wentian module|''Wentian'' laboratory module]].<ref name="reuters_wentian" />

== Operations ==
Since 5 June 2022, Tiangong has been a permanently crewed station, typically staffed with a crew of three but capable of supporting up to six people.<ref name="crew">{{cite news |url=https://english.news.cn/20220304/c76aa0bf18ac4bbe84ed79f42fd3c66f/c.html|title=China's space station to host 6 astronauts by end of 2022-Xinhua|access-date=31 March 2022|archive-date=26 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220326015209/https://english.news.cn/20220304/c76aa0bf18ac4bbe84ed79f42fd3c66f/c.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="shenzhou15_6">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/china-six-astronauts-space-station-at-once |title=China has 6 astronauts in space for the 1st time |website=Space.com |date=2 December 2022 |first=Andrew |last=Jones |access-date=4 December 2022 |archive-date=2 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221202155801/https://www.space.com/china-six-astronauts-space-station-at-once |url-status=live}}</ref> Operations are controlled from the [[Beijing Aerospace Flight Control Center]] in China.<ref name="China rolls out rocket for Tianzhou 2021" />

===Crewed missions===
{{Main|Shenzhou (spacecraft)}}

[[File:First gathering on Tiangong.jpg|thumb|alt=First gathering of two Chinese astronaut crews (Shenzhou 14 and 15) on Tiangong on 30 November 2022.|Two crews aboard Tiangong during the first handover, 30 November 2022]]
The first crewed mission to Tiangong, [[Shenzhou 12]], lasted 90 days, while missions from [[Shenzhou 13]] onward have typically lasted about 180 days.<ref>{{cite web|title=空间站建造后续有四次载人飞行，航天员每次在轨驻留3至6个月|url=https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_12457158|website=the paper|date=29 April 2021|access-date=18 August 2021|archive-date=20 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211120092452/https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_12457158|url-status=live}}</ref> Beginning with the transition between [[Shenzhou 14]] and [[Shenzhou 15]], overlapping "handover" periods have been used to ensure the station remains continuously inhabited.<ref name="shenzhou15_6" />

China maintains a contingency protocol—often described as "one launch, one on standby"—under which a Shenzhou spacecraft and [[Long March 2F]] rocket for the next planned mission are kept in a near-ready state at Jiuquan.<ref name="China rolls out rocket for Tianzhou 2021">{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/china-rolls-out-rocket-for-tianzhou-2-space-station-supply-mission/ |title=China rolls out rocket for Tianzhou-2 space station supply mission |date=17 May 2021 |access-date=13 June 2021 |archive-date=27 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221027154146/https://spacenews.com/china-rolls-out-rocket-for-tianzhou-2-space-station-supply-mission/ |url-status=live}}</ref> This capability was first used in 2025, when the [[Shenzhou 20]] crew was expected to return to Earth following the arrival of [[Shenzhou 21]]. Due to suspected [[space debris]] damage, the spacecraft’s return was delayed, and the crew instead returned on 14 November aboard Shenzhou 21 instead.<ref name="cnn">{{cite web | title=Chinese astronauts arrive home after suspected debris strike delays return to Earth | date=14 November 2025 | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2025/11/13/china/shenzhou-20-crew-return-earth-intl-hnk }}</ref> In turn, the launch of [[Shenzhou 22]], originally intended for the subsequent crew rotation, was launched months early to be available to the crew that arrived on Shenzhou 21.<ref name="Baptista 2025">{{Cite news |last=Baptista|first=Eduardo|date=25 November 2025|title=China completes first emergency mission to Tiangong space station|url=https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/china-launch-shenzhou-22-spaceship-0411-gmt-state-media-reports-2025-11-25/|access-date=26 November 2025|work=Reuters|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="Jones 2025">{{Cite news |last=Jones|first=Andrew|date=25 November 2025|title=Shenzhou-22 docks at Tiangong space station, resolving human spaceflight emergency|url=https://spacenews.com/shenzhou-22-docks-at-tiangong-space-station-resolving-human-spaceflight-emergency/|access-date=2 December 2025|work=[[SpaceNews]]}}</ref>

The CMSA is developing a next-generation crewed spacecraft, [[Mengzhou (spacecraft)|Mengzhou]], to eventually replace Shenzhou. The reusable capsule is designed for missions to both Tiangong and the Moon. It is larger than Shenzhou, can carry up to six or seven astronauts,<ref name="sfn_01">{{cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/05/08/chinas-next-generation-crew-spacecraft-lands-after-unpiloted-test-flight/|title=China's next-generation crew spacecraft lands after unpiloted test flight|website=Spaceflight Now|date=8 May 2020|access-date=26 May 2020|archive-date=27 November 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221127190235/https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/05/08/chinas-next-generation-crew-spacecraft-lands-after-unpiloted-test-flight/|url-status=live}}</ref> and includes cargo storage capable of returning materials to Earth—unlike Shenzhou or the Tianzhou cargo spacecraft.<ref name="sfn_01" /> The first uncrewed test flight of Mengzhou to Tiangong is expected in late 2026.

=== Cargo resupply ===
{{Main|Tianzhou (spacecraft)}}

[[File:Cargo loading diagram of Tianzhou.jpg|thumb|Cargo packages loaded on [[Tianzhou spacecraft]].]]

Tianzhou, a modified derivative of the Tiangong-1 spacecraft, is used as robotic cargo spacecraft to resupply this station.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://brahmand.com/news/China-completes-design-of-Tianzhou-cargo-spacecraft-/12805/1/10.html |title=China completes design of Tianzhou cargo spacecraft |date=9 September 2014 |author=BNS |publisher=Bramand Defence and Aerospace News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605151431/http://brahmand.com/news/China-completes-design-of-Tianzhou-cargo-spacecraft-/12805/1/10.html |archive-date=5 June 2015}}</ref> The launch mass of Tianzhou is around 13,000&nbsp;kg with a payload of around 6,000&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chinatopix.com/articles/9080/20140907/china-completes-first-cargo-spacecraft-design.htm |title=China Completes Design of First Cargo Spacecraft |date=7 September 2014 |author=Ana Verayo |publisher=China Topix |access-date=18 September 2014 |archive-date=1 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005259/http://www.chinatopix.com/articles/9080/20140907/china-completes-first-cargo-spacecraft-design.htm |url-status=live}}</ref> Launch, rendezvous and docking are fully autonomous, with mission control and crew used in override or monitoring roles.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/world/asia/china-plans-to-launch-tianzhou-cargo-ship-into-space-by-2016/ |publisher=Indian Express |title=China plans to launch Tianzhou cargo ship into space by 2016 |date=2 March 2014 |author=Press Trust of India |access-date=18 September 2014 |archive-date=20 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140920132400/http://indianexpress.com/article/world/asia/china-plans-to-launch-tianzhou-cargo-ship-into-space-by-2016/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In October 2024, CMSA awarded contracts to the [[Qingzhou (spacecraft)|''Qingzhou'']] cargo spacecraft, by [[CAS Space]], and the [[Spaceplane#China|''Haolong'']] [[spaceplane]], by [[Chengdu Aircraft Research and Design Institute]], to support the Tiangong space station.<ref name="z173">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Andrew |date=29 October 2024 |title=China chooses 2 teams to develop low-cost space station cargo spacecraft |url=https://spacenews.com/china-chooses-2-teams-to-develop-low-cost-space-station-cargo-spacecraft/ |access-date=13 May 2026 |website=SpaceNews}}</ref> On 30 March 2026, a prototype version of ''Qingzhou'' was launched on the maiden flight of CAS Space's [[Kinetica 2]] rocket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/chinas-kinetica-2-rocket-debuts-successfully-sending-prototype-cargo-spacecraft-to-orbit/|title=China’s Kinetica-2 rocket debuts successfully, sending prototype cargo spacecraft to orbit|website=SpaceNews}}</ref>

